ong the Rio Grande in Del Norte, Colorado.\nFile:DelNorteRiverWalk 100117 7.jpg|frame|Cottonwood trees in fall colors along the river walk.\nFile:PinosCreek 100117 2.jpg|frame|The South San Juan Mountains during the Autumn, just a few miles from town.\nFile:DN LookoutMtn 011720.jpg|frame|A trail marker along the School Loop of the Lookout Mountain trail system.\n\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|<!--Northern America-->|United States|Colorado}}\n*[[Outline of Colorado]]\n**[[Index of Colorado-related articles]]\n*[[State of Colorado]]\n**[[Colorado cities and towns]]\n***[[Colorado municipalities]]\n**[[Colorado counties]]\n***[[Rio Grande County, Colorado]]\n*[[San Luis Valley]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080418095558/http://www.cmca.gen.co.us/Municipality.cfm?MunicipalityID=91 Town of Del Norte contacts]\n*[http://dtdapps.coloradodot.info/staticdata/Downloads/CityMaps/DEL%20NORTE.pdf CDOT map of the Town of Del Norte]\n*[http://www.slvdweller.com SLV Dweller]\n\nDel Norte's major hospital is Rio Grande Hospital\n*[http://www.riograndehospital.org]\n\n{{Rio Grande County, Colorado}}\n{{Colorado|show}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Rio Grande County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Towns in Colorado]]\n[[Category:County seats in Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "C caudill1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Del_Norte,_Colorado"}
{"title_page": "Nine Radio", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Macquarie Radio Network|the formerly unrelated Macquarie Regional RadioWorks|Southern Cross Austereo|the parent company formerly operating as '''Macquarie Media Group'''|Southern Cross Media Group}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Nine Radio\n| logo             = \n| type             = Subsidiary\n| foundation       = {{bulleted list|{{start date|1938}} (as Macquarie Broadcasting Service)|{{start date|2015}} (as Nine Radio)}}\n| location_city    = [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]] (from 2020)\n| location_country = <br>[[Australia]]\n| key_people       = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[Nine Entertainment Co.]]\n| industry         = [[Broadcast radio]]\n| products         =\n| revenue          = \n| net_income       = \n| homepage         = {{URL|https://www.nineforbrands.com.au/brands/#radio|Nine Radio}}\n}}\n\n'''Nine Radio''' (formerly '''Macquarie Media Limited''') is an Australian media company, operating radio stations nationally in the capital cities of [[Sydney]], [[Melbourne]], [[Brisbane]] and [[Perth]], as well as regional [[Queensland]], it is based in the Sydney suburb of [[Pyrmont, New South Wales|Pyrmont]]. It was formerly a publicly listed company, but has been solely owned by [[Nine Entertainment Co.]] since 2019. It also operates the radio broadcast of [[Nine News (radio)|Nine News]]. The company was originally founded in 1938 as the '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''', adopting the name \"Macquarie Media\" after being acquired by [[Fairfax Media]] in 2015.\n\n== History ==\n=== Origins ===\n[[2GB]], one of [[Sydney]]'s premier commercial radio stations, was founded by Theosophical Broadcasting Station Pty Ltd. in 1926, a division of [[Theosophical Society Adyar]],  \nIn January 1936, in the depths of the [[Great Depression]], 2GB and [[2UE]] formed an alliance, '''Broadcasting Service Association''' (BSA), to share production facilities for producing radio drama and other locally produced entertainment, which was hugely popular and in better times highly lucrative. The BSA was under joint management of Alfred Edward Bennett and Cecil Vincent Stevenson, managing directors of 2GB and 2UE respectively.\nThat same year, the controlling interest in 2GB was purchased by Denison Estates Ltd. A new board of directors was appointed under chairman Sir [[Hugh Denison]] and included A. E. Bennett, who continued as station manager, and Frederick Daniell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17287755 |title=Station 2GB |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=30,847 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=13 November 1936 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn early February 1937 A. E. Bennett hosted a peak conference of commercial radio interests of New South Wales, Victoria and South Australia with a view to expanding the organisation into an inter-state network to secure additional outlets for their material. Those present included Sir John Butters, chairman of BSA, R. E. Denison and Frederick Daniell, representing Denison Estates Ltd.; V. F. Mitchell of [[4BC]] Brisbane; George Bennett, George Millar and Charles A. Fletcher of 2GB Sydney; C. V. Stevenson and Sydney E. Baume (brother of [[Eric Baume]])<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article236315119 |title=Eric Baume's Brother Suddenly Leaves Job |newspaper=[[Daily News (Sydney)]] |volume=1 |issue=31 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 January 1939 |accessdate=29 October 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> of 2UE Sydney; John T. Taylor of [[3AW]] Melbourne; Gordon Marsh of [[5DN]] Adelaide; Clive Ogilvy (often misspelled Ogilvie) and A. J. \"Jack\" Ryan of [[2CA]] Canberra; Russell A. Yeldon of [[2WL]] Wollongong; Eric and O. Robinson of [[2HR]] Hunter River; J. J. Armitage and D. R. Armstrong of Broadcasting Service Association Ltd.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230799639 |title=Radio Network System |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=8457 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 February 1937 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In November the same year Bennett was sacked<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article231124717 |title=Verdict for A. E. Bennett |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=9028 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=12 December 1938 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> by Denison and Butters from both his managerial position with 2GB and as a director of BSA, though public pronouncements had him resigning voluntarily. Harold Gordon Horner, New South Wales manager for the [[Australian Broadcasting Commission]], was appointed to take his place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article232015271 |title=Changes in 2GB |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=8696 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=17 November 1937 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n===Macquarie Broadcasting (1938\u20132015) ===\nIn July 1938 Sir Hugh Denison announced a further expansion and reorganisation of the company as the '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''' with a capital of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]250,000. The board consisted of Sir Hugh as chairman, Frederick Daniell as executive director, and George Millar as secretary; other founding directors were R. E. Denison, N. L. Shaw, C. Don Service, and S. S. Crick. H. G. Horner of 2GB, and C. V. Stevenson of 2UE were appointed advisory directors on broadcasting and technical matters respectively. George Anderson of [[2GZ]] was appointed network sales manager.  Affiliated stations in the new network were [[2CA]] Canberra; [[2GB]] and [[2UE]] Sydney; [[2WL]] South Coast; [[2HR]] Hunter River; [[3AW]] Melbourne; [[Ace Radio|3HA]] Hamilton; [[3TR]] Sale; [[3SH]] Swan Hill; [[4BH]] Brisbane; [[5DN]] Adelaide; [[5RM]] Renmark; [[6PR]] Perth; [[RadioWest|6KG]] Kalgoorlie. Head office was at Savoy House, 29 [[Bligh Street, Sydney]], and the Melbourne office at 37 [[Queen Street, Melbourne|Queen Street]].\n\nThe new company purchased the worldwide transcription business of 2GB and BSA and placed under the direction of Frederick Daniell, with sales managed by Clive Ogilvy and [[Grace Gibson]]. The BSA Players were reorganised as the Macquarie Players, with their recording studios \"Macquarie Productions\" at Pagewood and at 296 Pitt Street and 29 Bligh Street. Contracted actors included [[James Raglan]], [[Lou Vernon]], [[Peter Finch]], Betty Suttor and [[Harry Dearth]].<ref>Lane, Richard ''The Golden Age of Australian Radio Drama'' Melbourne University Press 1994 {{ISBN|0-522-84556-8}}</ref> The company became a major shareholder in Australian and New Zealand Theatres, Ltd., which had taken over the entertainment business [[J. C. Williamson, Ltd.]], and in Broadcast Enterprises, Ltd., of London. The Radio Theatre Guild was taken over as an organisation for training and developing talent. The record production, cutting and pressing business Featuradio was purchased and reorganised as Australian Record Company under management of Charles H. Gendle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229134023 |title=Radio Company Formed |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=1841 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 July 1938 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=15 (News Section) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFrom inception and until the early 1960s, the network was renowned for its high quality productions of variety programs, quizzes, dramas and serials. Most of these programs originated from Sydney. As well as being heard on all of the network's affiliates, right across the country, they were also syndicated to non-network stations. With the coming of television in 1956, the radio audience for these types of programs dropped dramatically. Macquarie stations solved the ''problem'' by quickly increasing their news, talk, commentary and current affairs content.<ref name=\"R.R. Walker 1973\">\"The Magic Spark\", R.R. Walker, 1973, The Hawthorn Press.</ref>\n\nIn 1973, a significant year because it was the 50th anniversary of broadcasting in Australia, the Macquarie Network had the following affiliates: 2GB Sydney; [[2CA]] Canberra; [[Parkes, New South Wales|2PK]] Parkes; [[96.5 Wave FM|2WL]] Wollongong; [[3AW]] Melbourne; [[Magic 882|4BH]] Brisbane; [[4BU]] Bundaberg; [[4GY]] Gympie; [[Cruise 1323|5DN]] Adelaide; [[6iX (radio station)|6IX]] Perth; [[RadioWest South West|6BY]] Bunbury; [[RadioWest|6MD]] Merredin; [[RadioWest|6WB]] Katanning; [[7HO FM|7HO]] Hobart.<ref name=\"R.R. Walker 1973\"/>\n\nDuring the 1930s, 40s, 50s, 60s and 70s, there were a number of other commercial radio networks, another key one being the [[Major Broadcasting Network|Major Network]]. Other former radio networks include: Federal Network; Associated Broadcasters of Australia; [[Amalgamated Wireless (Australasia)|AWA Broadcasting]]. There were also a number of State-based networks.\n\nBy the late 1980s Macquarie had become Australia's only national commercial radio network.  However, during the last three decades, a number of new networks have arisen, including the [[Macquarie Regional RadioWorks]], unrelated to the Macquarie Radio Network.  In 2007, 13 networks owned or controlled 80 per cent of the 261 Australian commercial radio stations<ref>''Changing Stations: The Story of Australian Commercial Radio'', Bridget Griffen-Foley, UNSW Press, 2009; referenced as ''Commercial Radio: A Snapshot'', CRA, Sydney, 2007</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Macquarie entered a joint venture with [[Pacific Star Network]] to relaunch Melbourne radio station [[3MP]] as [[Melbourne Talk Radio|MTR 1377]]. On 2 March 2012, MTR ceased operations when Pacific Star was unable to pay any monies owed to Macquarie.<ref name=noworries>{{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Ben|last2=Battersby|first2=Lucy|title='No worries' as MTR goes off the air|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/no-worries-as-mtr-goes-off-the-air-20120302-1u7ji.html|accessdate=5 March 2012|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=2 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304192120/http://www.theage.com.au/business/no-worries-as-mtr-goes-off-the-air-20120302-1u7ji.html|archive-date=4 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2011, Macquarie acquired the Smart Radio Network which encompasses [[4VL]], [[West FM (Queensland)|Triple C FM]], [[4HI]], [[4ZR]], [[4LM]], [[4SB]] and [[Hot Country]] network at a cost of $6 million. These stations are part of Macquarie Regional Radio, which is a wholly owned subsidiary of the Macquarie Radio Network.\n\n=== Macquarie Media (2015\u20132019) ===\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Macquarie Media Limited\n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Public company]] ({{ASX|MRN}})\n| foundation       = {{bulleted list|{{start date|1938}} (as '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''')|{{start date|2015}} (as '''Macquarie Media''')}}\n| defunct = {{End date|2020|01}}\n| location_city    = [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]]\n| location_country = [[Australia]]\n| key_people       = Adam Lang, Chief Operating Officer\n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = {{bulleted list|[[Nine Entertainment Co]] (90.6%)|Wilson Asset Management}}\n| industry         = [[Broadcast radio]]\n| products         =\n| revenue          = <!-- {{profit}} $ million [[AUD]] (2006) -->\n| net_income       = <!-- {{profit}} $ million [[AUD]] (2006) -->\n| homepage         = {{URL|https://web.archive.org/web/20091025080504/http://www.mrn.com.au/index.php|MRN}}\n}}\n\nIn December 2014, Macquarie announced that it had agreed to a [[Mergers and Acquisitions|merger]] with [[Fairfax Media#Radio|Fairfax Media]]. Under the deal, Fairfax gained a 55% share in the Macquarie Radio Network, with Macquarie's existing shareholders holding the remaining 45%.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Janda|first1=Michael|title=Fairfax and Macquarie to merge radio network|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-22/fairfax-macquarie-to-merge-radio-stations/5982594|accessdate=9 April 2015|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=22 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619142119/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-22/fairfax-macquarie-to-merge-radio-stations/5982594|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> To comply with legislation only allowing two radio licences to be held by one party in each market, stations [[2CH]] and [[4LM]] were sold;<ref>{{cite news|title=Macquarie Radio Network to sell two radio stations|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-sell-two-radio-stations|accessdate=9 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415153710/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-sell-two-radio-stations|archive-date=15 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and the merger was completed in March 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=And the deal is done...finally!|url=http://radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6698-and-the-deal-is-done-finally.html|accessdate=1 April 2015|work=Radio Today|date=31 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401003621/http://radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6698-and-the-deal-is-done-finally.html|archive-date=1 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MRN Fairfax merger complete|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-fairfax-merger-complete|accessdate=1 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=1 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150412/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-fairfax-merger-complete|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=aust-no-news>{{cite news |last1=Sinclair|first1=Lara |title=2UE News to go off air as newsroom merges with 2GB |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/ue-news-to-go-off-air-as-newsroom-merges-with-2gb/story-e6frg996-1227297386479 |accessdate=11 April 2015 |work=The Australian |agency=AAP |publisher=[[News Limited]] |date=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=fairfax-merge-macq>{{cite press release |title=COMPLETION OF FAIRFAX RADIO NETWORK MERGER WITH MACQUARIE RADIO NETWORK |url=http://www.fairfaxmedia.com.au/pressroom/au---nz-press-room/au---nz-press-room/completion-of-fairfax-radio-network-merger-with-macquarie-radio-network |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |accessdate=11 April 2015 |date=31 March 2015 |quote=Fairfax Media Limited ... today announced the completion of the merger of its Fairfax Radio Network ... with Macquarie Radio Network ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406174628/http://www.fairfaxmedia.com.au/pressroom/au---nz-press-room/au---nz-press-room/completion-of-fairfax-radio-network-merger-with-macquarie-radio-network |archive-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015 a number of programming changes occurred at Macquarie's stations. At [[4BC]] Brisbane, Breakfast presenters Ian Skippen and Loretta Ryan, Mornings host Patrick Condren, Nights host Walter Williams and Weekend Breakfast presenter Murray Shoring were dismissed, as well as sister [[Magic 882]] Nights' presenter Jo Henderson. In total, 18 positions were cut, and programming replaced by networked shows from 2GB and 2UE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4bc.com.au/news/media-statement-from-4bc-20150410-1migjp.html |title=Media Statement from 4BC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 April 2015 |website=4BC |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=10 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411115734/http://www.4bc.com.au/news/media-statement-from-4bc-20150410-1migjp.html |archivedate=11 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Axe falls at 4BC and Magic 882|url=http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6755-axe-falls-at-4bc.html|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=Radio Today|date=10 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413083147/http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6755-axe-falls-at-4bc.html|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Nathanael|title=Plug pulled on 4BC Brisbane boss|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/confidential/plug-pulled-on-4bc-brisbane-boss/story-fnn7l51k-1227302427595|accessdate=21 April 2015|work=[[The Courier-Mail]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=14 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414041939/http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/confidential/plug-pulled-on-4bc-brisbane-boss/story-fnn7l51k-1227302427595|archive-date=14 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In Sydney, [[2UE]]'s afternoon announcer [[Angela Catterns]] was dismissed, as was the entire newsroom, and the station's news services were replaced by the Macquarie's national news service<ref>{{cite news|last1=Christensen|first1=Nic|title=Macquarie/Fairfax Radio merger described as 'hostile takeover' as 2UE axes Angela Catterns|url=http://mumbrella.com.au/macquariefairfax-radio-merger-described-as-hostile-takeover-as-2ue-axes-angela-catterns-286646|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=mUmBRELLA|date=11 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413112734/http://mumbrella.com.au/macquariefairfax-radio-merger-described-as-hostile-takeover-as-2ue-axes-angela-catterns-286646|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> - while in Melbourne all of [[Magic 1278]]'s lineup and most of the production team was cut.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magic gone from Magic! Entire on air line-up sacked|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/magic-gone-magic-entire-air-line-sacked|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=13 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016191324/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/magic-gone-magic-entire-air-line-sacked|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2015 it was announced the company had divested its regional assets, selling eight radio stations to [[Resonate Broadcasting]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Queensland radio company triples its size with latest acquisition|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/queensland-radio-company-triples-its-size-latest-acquisition|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=30 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031123933/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/queensland-radio-company-triples-its-size-latest-acquisition|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Resonate buy MRN regional network|url=http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/7935-resonate-buy-mrn-regional-network.html|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=Radio Today|date=30 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031123716/http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/7935-resonate-buy-mrn-regional-network.html|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 November it was announced that all of Magic 882's programming - with the exception of nights - would be networked from [[Magic 1278]] in Melbourne.<ref>{{cite news|title=MRN announces changes to build a 'Magic Network'|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-announces-changes-build-magic-network|accessdate=8 November 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310030942/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-announces-changes-build-magic-network|archive-date=10 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2015 the company changed its name to '''Macquarie Media''' Limited.<ref>{{cite news|title=Macquarie Radio Network to change name|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-change-name|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=12 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063458/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-change-name|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following its merger with Fairfax in 2018, Nine acquired [[John Singleton (Australian entrepreneur)|John Singleton]]'s share in the company in 2019, increasing its stake in the company to 87%.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/companies/media-and-marketing/singleton-sells-macquarie-stake-to-nine-carnegie-expected-to-follow-20190924-p52u9l |title=Singleton sells Macquarie stake to Nine, Carnegie expected to follow |work=[[The Australian Financial Review]] |date=24 September 2019 |access-date= |author= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924052434/https://www.afr.com/companies/media-and-marketing/singleton-sells-macquarie-stake-to-nine-carnegie-expected-to-follow-20190924-p52u9l |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2019 Nine increased its shareholding to over 90% after purchasing stakes from Mark Carnegie (3.6 percent) and [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]] (1.3 percent) to allow Nine to compulsorily acquire the remaining shares.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/carnegie-cashes-his-stake-macquarie-media |title=Carnegie cashes in his stake in Macquarie Media |work=Radio Info |date=4 October 2019 |access-date=4 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004125635/https://radioinfo.com.au/news/carnegie-cashes-his-stake-macquarie-media |archive-date=4 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/nine-secures-takeover-of-macquarie-media-as-alan-jones-mark-carnegie-accept-offer-20191004-p52xl0.html |title=Nine secures takeover of Macquarie Media as Alan Jones, Mark Carnegie accept offer |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=4 October 2019 |access-date=4 October 2019 |author=Duke, Jennifer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004150810/https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/nine-secures-takeover-of-macquarie-media-as-alan-jones-mark-carnegie-accept-offer-20191004-p52xl0.html |archive-date=4 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2020, Nine confirmed that the Macquarie Media brand would be phased out.<ref>[https://mumbrella.com.au/nine-drops-macquarie-media-branding-for-radio-assets-612111 NEWSNine drops Macquarie Media branding for radio assets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106082136/https://mumbrella.com.au/nine-drops-macquarie-media-branding-for-radio-assets-612111 |date=6 January 2020 }} ''[[Mumbrella]]'' 6 January 2020</ref>\n\n=== Nine Radio (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn the 21st January 2020, new full owners Nine Entertainment Co. announced they would close the Macquarie Sports Radio brand in February and shift its stations towards 70s, 80s and 90s soft AC music, with stations returning to their previous names, albeit with revised logos.\n\n==Assets==\n===Nine Radio===\n====News. Talk. Sport.====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Callsign !! Frequency !! Location !! Format !! Notes\n|-\n| [[2GB]] || 873 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Sydney]], New South Wales || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[3AW]] || 693 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Melbourne]], Victoria || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[4BC]] || 1116 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Brisbane]], Queensland || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[6PR]] || 882 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Perth]], Western Australia || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| NTS || DAB+ 9A (Sydney)<br />DAB+ 9B || Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane and Perth || [[News talk]] || Formerly Fairfax Radio NTS\n|}\n\nNine Radio also manages national sales for [[NOVA Entertainment]] owned-and-operated [[5AA|FIVEaa]].\n\n==== Music ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Frequency !! Call-sign !! Location !! Format !! Former branding\n|-\n|[[2UE]]|| 954 AM<br />DAB+ 9A || 2UE || Sydney || 70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Macquarie Sports Radio & Talking Lifestyle\n|-\n|[[Magic 1278]]|| 1278 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || 3EE || Melbourne || 70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Macquarie Sports Radio & Talking Lifestyle\n|-\n|[[4BH]]\n|882 AM<br />DAB+ 9B\n|4BH\n|Brisbane\n|70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Magic 882, Macquarie Sports Radio  & Talking Lifestyle\n|}\n\n====Former stations====\nThe following stations were formerly owned-and-operated by Macquarie but have been divested since 2012.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Frequency !! Location !! Format !! Fate !! Notes\n|-\n| [[MTR 1377]] || 1377 AM<br />DAB+ 9A || [[Melbourne, Victoria]] || [[News talk]] || Closed in 2012. The station, call-sign 3MP, reverted to being a music station under the marketing name of [[Classic Rock Radio]] || Joint venture with [[Pacific Star Network]]\n|-\n| Hot Country Radio || 1611 AM || [[Dalby, Queensland]] || [[Country music]] || Sold to [[Resonate Broadcasting]] in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[2CH]] || 1170 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Sydney, New South Wales]] || [[Oldies]]<br />[[Easy listening]] || Due to ACMA regulation, in January 2017 the station was sold to a consortium of Oceania Capital Partners, [[Glenn Wheatley]] and John Williams ||\n|-\n| [[West FM (Queensland)|Triple C FM]] || 101.7 FM ||[[Charleville, Queensland]] || [[Adult contemporary]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4HI]] || 1143 AM || [[Emerald, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4LM]] || 666 AM || [[Mount Isa]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4SB]] || 1071 AM || [[Kingaroy, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4VL]] || 918 AM || [[Charleville, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4ZR]] || 1476 AM || [[Roma, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091025080504/http://www.mrn.com.au/index.php Macquarie Media Limited website] (archived)\n*[http://www.2gb.com.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=49&Itemid=241 Macquarie National News]\n\n{{National radio networks in Australia}}\n{{Nine Entertainment}}\n\n[[Category:Macquarie Media|*]]\n[[Category:Australian radio networks]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Nine Entertainment Co.]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Macquarie Radio Network|the formerly unrelated Macquarie Regional RadioWorks|Southern Cross Austereo|the parent company formerly operating as '''Macquarie Media Group'''|Southern Cross Media Group}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Nine Radio\n| logo             = \n| type             = Subsidiary\n| foundation       = {{bulleted list|{{start date|1938}} (as Macquarie Broadcasting Service)|{{start date|2015}} (as Nine Radio)}}\n| location_city    = [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]] (from 2020)\n| location_country = <br>[[Australia]]\n| key_people       = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[Nine Entertainment Co.]]\n| industry         = [[Broadcast radio]]\n| products         =\n| revenue          = \n| net_income       = \n| homepage         = {{URL|https://www.nineforbrands.com.au/brands/#radio|Nine Radio}}\n}}\n\n'''Nine Radio''' (formerly '''Macquarie Media Limited''') is an Australian media company, operating radio stations nationally in the capital cities of [[Sydney]], [[Melbourne]], [[Brisbane]] and [[Perth]], as well as regional [[Queensland]], it is based in the Sydney suburb of [[Pyrmont, New South Wales|Pyrmont]]. It was formerly a publicly listed company, but has been solely owned by [[Nine Entertainment Co.]] since 2019. It also operates the radio broadcast of [[Nine News (radio)|Nine News]]. The company was originally founded in 1938 as the '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''', adopting the name \"Macquarie Media\" after being acquired by [[Fairfax Media]] in 2015.\n\n== History ==\n=== Origins ===\n[[2GB]], one of [[Sydney]]'s premier commercial radio stations, was founded by Theosophical Broadcasting Station Pty Ltd. in 1926, a division of [[Theosophical Society Adyar]],  \nIn January 1936, in the depths of the [[Great Depression]], 2GB and [[2UE]] formed an alliance, '''Broadcasting Service Association''' (BSA), to share production facilities for producing radio drama and other locally produced entertainment, which was hugely popular and in better times highly lucrative. The BSA was under joint management of Alfred Edward Bennett and Cecil Vincent Stevenson, managing directors of 2GB and 2UE respectively.\nThat same year, the controlling interest in 2GB was purchased by Denison Estates Ltd. A new board of directors was appointed under chairman Sir [[Hugh Denison]] and included A. E. Bennett, who continued as station manager, and Frederick Daniell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17287755 |title=Station 2GB |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=30,847 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=13 November 1936 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn early February 1937 A. E. Bennett hosted a peak conference of commercial radio interests of New South Wales, Victoria and South Australia with a view to expanding the organisation into an inter-state network to secure additional outlets for their material. Those present included Sir John Butters, chairman of BSA, R. E. Denison and Frederick Daniell, representing Denison Estates Ltd.; V. F. Mitchell of [[4BC]] Brisbane; George Bennett, George Millar and Charles A. Fletcher of 2GB Sydney; C. V. Stevenson and Sydney E. Baume (brother of [[Eric Baume]])<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article236315119 |title=Eric Baume's Brother Suddenly Leaves Job |newspaper=[[Daily News (Sydney)]] |volume=1 |issue=31 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 January 1939 |accessdate=29 October 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> of 2UE Sydney; John T. Taylor of [[3AW]] Melbourne; Gordon Marsh of [[5DN]] Adelaide; Clive Ogilvy (often misspelled Ogilvie) and A. J. \"Jack\" Ryan of [[2CA]] Canberra; Russell A. Yeldon of [[2WL]] Wollongong; Eric and O. Robinson of [[2HR]] Hunter River; J. J. Armitage and D. R. Armstrong of Broadcasting Service Association Ltd.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230799639 |title=Radio Network System |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=8457 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 February 1937 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In November the same year Bennett was sacked<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article231124717 |title=Verdict for A. E. Bennett |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=9028 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=12 December 1938 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> by Denison and Butters from both his managerial position with 2GB and as a director of BSA, though public pronouncements had him resigning voluntarily. Harold Gordon Horner, New South Wales manager for the [[Australian Broadcasting Commission]], was appointed to take his place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article232015271 |title=Changes in 2GB |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=8696 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=17 November 1937 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n===Macquarie Broadcasting (1938\u20132015) ===\nIn July 1938 Sir Hugh Denison announced a further expansion and reorganisation of the company as the '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''' with a capital of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]250,000. The board consisted of Sir Hugh as chairman, Frederick Daniell as executive director, and George Millar as secretary; other founding directors were R. E. Denison, N. L. Shaw, C. Don Service, and S. S. Crick. H. G. Horner of 2GB, and C. V. Stevenson of 2UE were appointed advisory directors on broadcasting and technical matters respectively. George Anderson of [[2GZ]] was appointed network sales manager.  Affiliated stations in the new network were [[2CA]] Canberra; [[2GB]] and [[2UE]] Sydney; [[2WL]] South Coast; [[2HR]] Hunter River; [[3AW]] Melbourne; [[Ace Radio|3HA]] Hamilton; [[3TR]] Sale; [[3SH]] Swan Hill; [[4BH]] Brisbane; [[5DN]] Adelaide; [[5RM]] Renmark; [[6PR]] Perth; [[RadioWest|6KG]] Kalgoorlie. Head office was at Savoy House, 29 [[Bligh Street, Sydney]], and the Melbourne office at 37 [[Queen Street, Melbourne|Queen Street]].\n\nThe new company purchased the worldwide transcription business of 2GB and BSA and placed under the direction of Frederick Daniell, with sales managed by Clive Ogilvy and [[Grace Gibson]]. The BSA Players were reorganised as the Macquarie Players, with their recording studios \"Macquarie Productions\" at Pagewood and at 296 Pitt Street and 29 Bligh Street. Contracted actors included [[James Raglan]], [[Lou Vernon]], [[Peter Finch]], Betty Suttor and [[Harry Dearth]].<ref>Lane, Richard ''The Golden Age of Australian Radio Drama'' Melbourne University Press 1994 {{ISBN|0-522-84556-8}}</ref> The company became a major shareholder in Australian and New Zealand Theatres, Ltd., which had taken over the entertainment business [[J. C. Williamson, Ltd.]], and in Broadcast Enterprises, Ltd., of London. The Radio Theatre Guild was taken over as an organisation for training and developing talent. The record production, cutting and pressing business Featuradio was purchased and reorganised as Australian Record Company under management of Charles H. Gendle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229134023 |title=Radio Company Formed |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)]] |issue=1841 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 July 1938 |accessdate=28 October 2017 |page=15 (News Section) |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFrom inception and until the early 1960s, the network was renowned for its high quality productions of variety programs, quizzes, dramas and serials. Most of these programs originated from Sydney. As well as being heard on all of the network's affiliates, right across the country, they were also syndicated to non-network stations. With the coming of television in 1956, the radio audience for these types of programs dropped dramatically. Macquarie stations solved the ''problem'' by quickly increasing their news, talk, commentary and current affairs content.<ref name=\"R.R. Walker 1973\">\"The Magic Spark\", R.R. Walker, 1973, The Hawthorn Press.</ref>\n\nIn 1973, a significant year because it was the 50th anniversary of broadcasting in Australia, the Macquarie Network had the following affiliates: 2GB Sydney; [[2CA]] Canberra; [[Parkes, New South Wales|2PK]] Parkes; [[96.5 Wave FM|2WL]] Wollongong; [[3AW]] Melbourne; [[Magic 882|4BH]] Brisbane; [[4BU]] Bundaberg; [[4GY]] Gympie; [[Cruise 1323|5DN]] Adelaide; [[6iX (radio station)|6IX]] Perth; [[RadioWest South West|6BY]] Bunbury; [[RadioWest|6MD]] Merredin; [[RadioWest|6WB]] Katanning; [[7HO FM|7HO]] Hobart.<ref name=\"R.R. Walker 1973\"/>\n\nDuring the 1930s, 40s, 50s, 60s and 70s, there were a number of other commercial radio networks, another key one being the [[Major Broadcasting Network|Major Network]]. Other former radio networks include: Federal Network; Associated Broadcasters of Australia; [[Amalgamated Wireless (Australasia)|AWA Broadcasting]]. There were also a number of State-based networks.\n\nBy the late 1980s Macquarie had become Australia's only national commercial radio network.  However, during the last three decades, a number of new networks have arisen, including the [[Macquarie Regional RadioWorks]], unrelated to the Macquarie Radio Network.  In 2007, 13 networks owned or controlled 80 per cent of the 261 Australian commercial radio stations<ref>''Changing Stations: The Story of Australian Commercial Radio'', Bridget Griffen-Foley, UNSW Press, 2009; referenced as ''Commercial Radio: A Snapshot'', CRA, Sydney, 2007</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Macquarie entered a joint venture with [[Pacific Star Network]] to relaunch Melbourne radio station [[3MP]] as [[Melbourne Talk Radio|MTR 1377]]. On 2 March 2012, MTR ceased operations when Pacific Star was unable to pay any monies owed to Macquarie.<ref name=noworries>{{cite news|last1=Butler|first1=Ben|last2=Battersby|first2=Lucy|title='No worries' as MTR goes off the air|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/no-worries-as-mtr-goes-off-the-air-20120302-1u7ji.html|accessdate=5 March 2012|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=2 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304192120/http://www.theage.com.au/business/no-worries-as-mtr-goes-off-the-air-20120302-1u7ji.html|archive-date=4 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2011, Macquarie acquired the Smart Radio Network which encompasses [[4VL]], [[West FM (Queensland)|Triple C FM]], [[4HI]], [[4ZR]], [[4LM]], [[4SB]] and [[Hot Country]] network at a cost of $6 million. These stations are part of Macquarie Regional Radio, which is a wholly owned subsidiary of the Macquarie Radio Network.\n\n=== Macquarie Media (2015\u20132019) ===\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Macquarie Media Limited\n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Public company]] ({{ASX|MRN}})\n| foundation       = {{bulleted list|{{start date|1938}} (as '''Macquarie Broadcasting Service''')|{{start date|2015}} (as '''Macquarie Media''')}}\n| defunct = {{End date|2020|01}}\n| location_city    = [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]]\n| location_country = <br>[[Australia]]\n| key_people       = Adam Lang, Chief Operating Officer\n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = {{bulleted list|[[Nine Entertainment Co]] (90.6%)|Wilson Asset Management}}\n| industry         = [[Broadcast radio]]\n| products         =\n| revenue          = <!-- {{profit}} $ million [[AUD]] (2006) -->\n| net_income       = <!-- {{profit}} $ million [[AUD]] (2006) -->\n| homepage         = {{URL|https://web.archive.org/web/20091025080504/http://www.mrn.com.au/index.php|MRN}}\n}}\n\nIn December 2014, Macquarie announced that it had agreed to a [[Mergers and Acquisitions|merger]] with [[Fairfax Media#Radio|Fairfax Media]]. Under the deal, Fairfax gained a 55% share in the Macquarie Radio Network, with Macquarie's existing shareholders holding the remaining 45%.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Janda|first1=Michael|title=Fairfax and Macquarie to merge radio network|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-22/fairfax-macquarie-to-merge-radio-stations/5982594|accessdate=9 April 2015|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=22 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619142119/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-22/fairfax-macquarie-to-merge-radio-stations/5982594|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> To comply with legislation only allowing two radio licences to be held by one party in each market, stations [[2CH]] and [[4LM]] were sold;<ref>{{cite news|title=Macquarie Radio Network to sell two radio stations|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-sell-two-radio-stations|accessdate=9 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=2 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415153710/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-sell-two-radio-stations|archive-date=15 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and the merger was completed in March 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=And the deal is done...finally!|url=http://radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6698-and-the-deal-is-done-finally.html|accessdate=1 April 2015|work=Radio Today|date=31 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401003621/http://radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6698-and-the-deal-is-done-finally.html|archive-date=1 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MRN Fairfax merger complete|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-fairfax-merger-complete|accessdate=1 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=1 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150412/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-fairfax-merger-complete|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=aust-no-news>{{cite news |last1=Sinclair|first1=Lara |title=2UE News to go off air as newsroom merges with 2GB |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/ue-news-to-go-off-air-as-newsroom-merges-with-2gb/story-e6frg996-1227297386479 |accessdate=11 April 2015 |work=The Australian |agency=AAP |publisher=[[News Limited]] |date=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=fairfax-merge-macq>{{cite press release |title=COMPLETION OF FAIRFAX RADIO NETWORK MERGER WITH MACQUARIE RADIO NETWORK |url=http://www.fairfaxmedia.com.au/pressroom/au---nz-press-room/au---nz-press-room/completion-of-fairfax-radio-network-merger-with-macquarie-radio-network |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |accessdate=11 April 2015 |date=31 March 2015 |quote=Fairfax Media Limited ... today announced the completion of the merger of its Fairfax Radio Network ... with Macquarie Radio Network ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406174628/http://www.fairfaxmedia.com.au/pressroom/au---nz-press-room/au---nz-press-room/completion-of-fairfax-radio-network-merger-with-macquarie-radio-network |archive-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015 a number of programming changes occurred at Macquarie's stations. At [[4BC]] Brisbane, Breakfast presenters Ian Skippen and Loretta Ryan, Mornings host Patrick Condren, Nights host Walter Williams and Weekend Breakfast presenter Murray Shoring were dismissed, as well as sister [[Magic 882]] Nights' presenter Jo Henderson. In total, 18 positions were cut, and programming replaced by networked shows from 2GB and 2UE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4bc.com.au/news/media-statement-from-4bc-20150410-1migjp.html |title=Media Statement from 4BC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 April 2015 |website=4BC |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=10 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411115734/http://www.4bc.com.au/news/media-statement-from-4bc-20150410-1migjp.html |archivedate=11 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Axe falls at 4BC and Magic 882|url=http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6755-axe-falls-at-4bc.html|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=Radio Today|date=10 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413083147/http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/6755-axe-falls-at-4bc.html|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Nathanael|title=Plug pulled on 4BC Brisbane boss|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/confidential/plug-pulled-on-4bc-brisbane-boss/story-fnn7l51k-1227302427595|accessdate=21 April 2015|work=[[The Courier-Mail]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=14 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414041939/http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/confidential/plug-pulled-on-4bc-brisbane-boss/story-fnn7l51k-1227302427595|archive-date=14 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In Sydney, [[2UE]]'s afternoon announcer [[Angela Catterns]] was dismissed, as was the entire newsroom, and the station's news services were replaced by the Macquarie's national news service<ref>{{cite news|last1=Christensen|first1=Nic|title=Macquarie/Fairfax Radio merger described as 'hostile takeover' as 2UE axes Angela Catterns|url=http://mumbrella.com.au/macquariefairfax-radio-merger-described-as-hostile-takeover-as-2ue-axes-angela-catterns-286646|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=mUmBRELLA|date=11 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413112734/http://mumbrella.com.au/macquariefairfax-radio-merger-described-as-hostile-takeover-as-2ue-axes-angela-catterns-286646|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> - while in Melbourne all of [[Magic 1278]]'s lineup and most of the production team was cut.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magic gone from Magic! Entire on air line-up sacked|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/magic-gone-magic-entire-air-line-sacked|accessdate=13 April 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=13 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016191324/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/magic-gone-magic-entire-air-line-sacked|archive-date=16 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2015 it was announced the company had divested its regional assets, selling eight radio stations to [[Resonate Broadcasting]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Queensland radio company triples its size with latest acquisition|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/queensland-radio-company-triples-its-size-latest-acquisition|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=30 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031123933/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/queensland-radio-company-triples-its-size-latest-acquisition|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Resonate buy MRN regional network|url=http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/7935-resonate-buy-mrn-regional-network.html|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=Radio Today|date=30 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031123716/http://www.radiotoday.com.au/news/whats-new/7935-resonate-buy-mrn-regional-network.html|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 November it was announced that all of Magic 882's programming - with the exception of nights - would be networked from [[Magic 1278]] in Melbourne.<ref>{{cite news|title=MRN announces changes to build a 'Magic Network'|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-announces-changes-build-magic-network|accessdate=8 November 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310030942/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/mrn-announces-changes-build-magic-network|archive-date=10 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2015 the company changed its name to '''Macquarie Media''' Limited.<ref>{{cite news|title=Macquarie Radio Network to change name|url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-change-name|accessdate=25 October 2015|work=Radioinfo.com.au|date=12 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063458/https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/macquarie-radio-network-change-name|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following its merger with Fairfax in 2018, Nine acquired [[John Singleton (Australian entrepreneur)|John Singleton]]'s share in the company in 2019, increasing its stake in the company to 87%.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.afr.com/companies/media-and-marketing/singleton-sells-macquarie-stake-to-nine-carnegie-expected-to-follow-20190924-p52u9l |title=Singleton sells Macquarie stake to Nine, Carnegie expected to follow |work=[[The Australian Financial Review]] |date=24 September 2019 |access-date= |author= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924052434/https://www.afr.com/companies/media-and-marketing/singleton-sells-macquarie-stake-to-nine-carnegie-expected-to-follow-20190924-p52u9l |archive-date=24 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2019 Nine increased its shareholding to over 90% after purchasing stakes from Mark Carnegie (3.6 percent) and [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]] (1.3 percent) to allow Nine to compulsorily acquire the remaining shares.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/carnegie-cashes-his-stake-macquarie-media |title=Carnegie cashes in his stake in Macquarie Media |work=Radio Info |date=4 October 2019 |access-date=4 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004125635/https://radioinfo.com.au/news/carnegie-cashes-his-stake-macquarie-media |archive-date=4 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/nine-secures-takeover-of-macquarie-media-as-alan-jones-mark-carnegie-accept-offer-20191004-p52xl0.html |title=Nine secures takeover of Macquarie Media as Alan Jones, Mark Carnegie accept offer |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=4 October 2019 |access-date=4 October 2019 |author=Duke, Jennifer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004150810/https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/nine-secures-takeover-of-macquarie-media-as-alan-jones-mark-carnegie-accept-offer-20191004-p52xl0.html |archive-date=4 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2020, Nine confirmed that the Macquarie Media brand would be phased out.<ref>[https://mumbrella.com.au/nine-drops-macquarie-media-branding-for-radio-assets-612111 NEWSNine drops Macquarie Media branding for radio assets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106082136/https://mumbrella.com.au/nine-drops-macquarie-media-branding-for-radio-assets-612111 |date=6 January 2020 }} ''[[Mumbrella]]'' 6 January 2020</ref>\n\n=== Nine Radio (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn the 21st January 2020, new full owners Nine Entertainment Co. announced they would close the Macquarie Sports Radio brand in February and shift its stations towards 70s, 80s and 90s soft AC music, with stations returning to their previous names, albeit with revised logos.\n\n==Assets==\n===Nine Radio===\n====News. Talk. Sport.====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Callsign !! Frequency !! Location !! Format !! Notes\n|-\n| [[2GB]] || 873 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Sydney]], New South Wales || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[3AW]] || 693 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Melbourne]], Victoria || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[4BC]] || 1116 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Brisbane]], Queensland || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| [[6PR]] || 882 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Perth]], Western Australia || [[News talk]] ||\n|-\n| NTS || DAB+ 9A (Sydney)<br />DAB+ 9B || Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane and Perth || [[News talk]] || Formerly Fairfax Radio NTS\n|}\n\nNine Radio also manages national sales for [[NOVA Entertainment]] owned-and-operated [[5AA|FIVEaa]].\n\n==== Music ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Frequency !! Call-sign !! Location !! Format !! Former branding\n|-\n|[[2UE]]|| 954 AM<br />DAB+ 9A || 2UE || Sydney || 70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Macquarie Sports Radio & Talking Lifestyle\n|-\n|[[Magic 1278]]|| 1278 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || 3EE || Melbourne || 70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Macquarie Sports Radio & Talking Lifestyle\n|-\n|[[4BH]]\n|882 AM<br />DAB+ 9B\n|4BH\n|Brisbane\n|70s, 80s and 90s music\n|Magic 882, Macquarie Sports Radio  & Talking Lifestyle\n|}\n\n====Former stations====\nThe following stations were formerly owned-and-operated by Macquarie but have been divested since 2012.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Frequency !! Location !! Format !! Fate !! Notes\n|-\n| [[MTR 1377]] || 1377 AM<br />DAB+ 9A || [[Melbourne, Victoria]] || [[News talk]] || Closed in 2012. The station, call-sign 3MP, reverted to being a music station under the marketing name of [[Classic Rock Radio]] || Joint venture with [[Pacific Star Network]]\n|-\n| Hot Country Radio || 1611 AM || [[Dalby, Queensland]] || [[Country music]] || Sold to [[Resonate Broadcasting]] in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[2CH]] || 1170 AM<br />DAB+ 9B || [[Sydney, New South Wales]] || [[Oldies]]<br />[[Easy listening]] || Due to ACMA regulation, in January 2017 the station was sold to a consortium of Oceania Capital Partners, [[Glenn Wheatley]] and John Williams ||\n|-\n| [[West FM (Queensland)|Triple C FM]] || 101.7 FM ||[[Charleville, Queensland]] || [[Adult contemporary]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4HI]] || 1143 AM || [[Emerald, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4LM]] || 666 AM || [[Mount Isa]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4SB]] || 1071 AM || [[Kingaroy, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4VL]] || 918 AM || [[Charleville, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|-\n| [[4ZR]] || 1476 AM || [[Roma, Queensland]] || [[Classic hits]] || Sold to Resonate Broadcasting in November 2015 ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091025080504/http://www.mrn.com.au/index.php Macquarie Media Limited website] (archived)\n*[http://www.2gb.com.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=49&Itemid=241 Macquarie National News]\n\n{{National radio networks in Australia}}\n{{Nine Entertainment}}\n\n[[Category:Macquarie Media|*]]\n[[Category:Australian radio networks]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Nine Entertainment Co.]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Heyitsstevo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMacquarie Media (2015\u20132019)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nine_Radio"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari\n| office           = Punjab Minister for Irrigation\n| term_start       = 27 August 2018\n| term_end         = \n| office1          = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]]\n| term_start1      = 15 August 2018\n| term_end1        = \n| constituency1    = PP-293 (Rajanpur-I)\n| term_start2      = 2003\n| term_end2        = 2012\n| office3          = Member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]]\n| term_start3      = March 2012\n| term_end3        = March 2018\n| party            = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n| image            = Muhammad Mohsin Leghari.jpg\n| appointer        = Punjab Chief Minister\n| assembly         = Punjab Assembly\n| preceded         = Amanat Ullah Khan Shadikhel\n| birth_place      = Pakistan\n}}\n\n'''Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0645\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u063a\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}}}; born 9 June 1963) is a Pakistani politician who is the current Provincial Minister of Punjab for Irrigation, in office since 27 August 2018. He has been a member of [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]], since August 2018. Previously he was a member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]] from March 2012 to March 2018 and a member of the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab from 2003 to 2012.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born on 9 June 1963 in [[Dera Ghazi Khan]].<ref name=\"senate/profile\">{{cite web|title=Profile|url=http://www.senate.gov.pk/en/profile.php?uid=787&catid=&subcatid=&cattitle=|website=www.senate.gov.pk|publisher=Senate of Pakistan|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904193042/http://www.senate.gov.pk/en/profile.php?uid=787&catid=&subcatid=&cattitle=|archivedate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pap/2002\" />\n\nHe received his early education from [[Aitchison College]]. He did Post graduate Diploma in Applied Economics from the [[University of the Punjab]].<ref name=\"senate/profile\" /> He holds the degree of Bachelor of Arts.<ref name=\"pap/2008\">{{cite web|title=Punjab Assembly|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/669|website=www.pap.gov.pk|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224012203/http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/669|archivedate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] as a candidate of [[National Alliance (Pakistan)|National Alliance]] from Constituency PP-245 (Dera Ghazi Khan-VI) in bye-elections held in 2003.<ref name=\"pap/2002\">{{cite web|title=Punjab Assembly|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/9/254|website=www.pap.gov.pk|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111174422/http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/9/254|archivedate=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was re-elected to the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab as a candidate of  [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]] from Constituency PP-245 (Dera Ghazi Khan-VI) in [[2008 Pakistani general election]].<ref name=\"pap/2008\" /> In 2012, he resigned from his seat in the Punjab Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunya News: Pakistan:-Polling continues in PP 243, PP 245 ...|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/World/78961-Occupy-Frankfurt-protesters-show-discontent-over-f|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=dunyanews.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128154528/http://dunyanews.tv/en/World/78961-Occupy-Frankfurt-protesters-show-discontent-over-f|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[Senate of Pakistan]] as an independent candidate in [[2012 Pakistani Senate election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PPP, allies sweep Senate polls|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2012/03/03/ppp-allies-sweep-senate-polls/|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128154527/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2012/03/03/ppp-allies-sweep-senate-polls/|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Iftikhar A.|title=Ruling coalition gains a foothold in Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/699805/ppp-bags-19-seats-ruling-coalition-gains-a-foothold-in-senate|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=3 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508211733/http://www.dawn.com/news/699805/ppp-bags-19-seats-ruling-coalition-gains-a-foothold-in-senate|archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate: Nayyer, Baloch elected unopposed|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/41230-senate-nayyer-baloch-elected-unopposed|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=www.geo.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729062817/https://www.geo.tv/latest/41230-senate-nayyer-baloch-elected-unopposed|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref> His Senate membership was due to expire in March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senate to elect 52 new members on March 3 |url=https://nation.com.pk/30-Jan-2018/senate-to-elect-52-new-members-on-march-3 |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=The Nation |date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was re-elected to the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab as a candidate of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] (PTI) from Constituency PP-293 (Rajanpur-I) in [[2018 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PP-293 Result - Election Results 2018 -  Rajanpur 1  - PP-293 Candidates - PP-293 Constituency Details - thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/election/constituency/PP-293 |website=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=28 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2018, he submitted a resolution in the Punjab Assembly demanding creation of Southern Punjab, a separate province.<ref>{{cite news |first=Arif |last=Malik |title=PTI lawmaker submits resolution for south Punjab in provincial assembly |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1427151/pti-lawmaker-submits-resolution-for-south-punjab-in-provincial-assembly |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=dawn.com |date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2018, he was inducted into the provincial Punjab cabinet of Chief Minister [[Sardar Usman Buzdar]] and was appointed as Minister for Irrigation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab\u2019s 23-member cabinet sworn in |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/08/27/punjabs-23-member-cabinet-sworn-in/ |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk |date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan Leghari, Muhammad Mohsin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani senators (14th Parliament)]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Punjab MPAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Punjab MPAs 2008\u20132013]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Punjab)]]\n[[Category:Provincial ministers of Punjab]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari\n| office              = Punjab Minister for Irrigation\n| term_start          = 27 August 2018|term_end\n| office1             = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]]\n| term_start1         = 15 August 2018\n| term_end1           = \n| constituency1       = PP-293 (Rajanpur-I)\n| term_start2         = 2003\n| term_end2           = 2012\n| office3             = Member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]]\n| term_start3         = March 2012\n| term_end3           = March 2018\n| nationality         = Pakistani\n| party               = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n| image               = [[File:Muhammad Mohsin Leghari.jpg|thumb|]]\n| appointer           = Punjab Chief Minister\n| assembly            = Punjab Assembly\n| preceded            = Amanat Ullah Khan Shadikhel\n}}\n\n'''Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0645\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u063a\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}}}; born 9 June 1963) is a Pakistani politician who is the current Provincial Minister of Punjab for Irrigation, in office since 27 August 2018. He has been a member of [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]], since August 2018. Previously he was a member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]] from March 2012 to March 2018 and a member of the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab from 2003 to 2012.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born on 9 June 1963 in [[Dera Ghazi Khan]].<ref name=\"senate/profile\">{{cite web|title=Profile|url=http://www.senate.gov.pk/en/profile.php?uid=787&catid=&subcatid=&cattitle=|website=www.senate.gov.pk|publisher=Senate of Pakistan|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904193042/http://www.senate.gov.pk/en/profile.php?uid=787&catid=&subcatid=&cattitle=|archivedate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pap/2002\" />\n\nHe received his early education from [[Aitchison College]]. He did Post graduate Diploma in Applied Economics from the [[University of the Punjab]].<ref name=\"senate/profile\" /> He holds the degree of Bachelor of Arts.<ref name=\"pap/2008\">{{cite web|title=Punjab Assembly|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/669|website=www.pap.gov.pk|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224012203/http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/669|archivedate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] as a candidate of [[National Alliance (Pakistan)|National Alliance]] from Constituency PP-245 (Dera Ghazi Khan-VI) in bye-elections held in 2003.<ref name=\"pap/2002\">{{cite web|title=Punjab Assembly|url=http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/9/254|website=www.pap.gov.pk|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111174422/http://www.pap.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/9/254|archivedate=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was re-elected to the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab as a candidate of  [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]] from Constituency PP-245 (Dera Ghazi Khan-VI) in [[2008 Pakistani general election]].<ref name=\"pap/2008\" /> In 2012, he resigned from his seat in the Punjab Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunya News: Pakistan:-Polling continues in PP 243, PP 245 ...|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/World/78961-Occupy-Frankfurt-protesters-show-discontent-over-f|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=dunyanews.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128154528/http://dunyanews.tv/en/World/78961-Occupy-Frankfurt-protesters-show-discontent-over-f|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[Senate of Pakistan]] as an independent candidate in [[2012 Pakistani Senate election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PPP, allies sweep Senate polls|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2012/03/03/ppp-allies-sweep-senate-polls/|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128154527/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2012/03/03/ppp-allies-sweep-senate-polls/|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Iftikhar A.|title=Ruling coalition gains a foothold in Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/699805/ppp-bags-19-seats-ruling-coalition-gains-a-foothold-in-senate|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=3 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508211733/http://www.dawn.com/news/699805/ppp-bags-19-seats-ruling-coalition-gains-a-foothold-in-senate|archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate: Nayyer, Baloch elected unopposed|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/41230-senate-nayyer-baloch-elected-unopposed|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=www.geo.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729062817/https://www.geo.tv/latest/41230-senate-nayyer-baloch-elected-unopposed|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref> His Senate membership was due to expire in March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senate to elect 52 new members on March 3 |url=https://nation.com.pk/30-Jan-2018/senate-to-elect-52-new-members-on-march-3 |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=The Nation |date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was re-elected to the Provincial Assembly of the Punjab as a candidate of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] (PTI) from Constituency PP-293 (Rajanpur-I) in [[2018 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PP-293 Result - Election Results 2018 -  Rajanpur 1  - PP-293 Candidates - PP-293 Constituency Details - thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/election/constituency/PP-293 |website=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=28 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2018, he submitted a resolution in the Punjab Assembly demanding creation of Southern Punjab, a separate province.<ref>{{cite news |first=Arif |last=Malik |title=PTI lawmaker submits resolution for south Punjab in provincial assembly |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1427151/pti-lawmaker-submits-resolution-for-south-punjab-in-provincial-assembly |accessdate=15 August 2018 |work=dawn.com |date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2018, he was inducted into the provincial Punjab cabinet of Chief Minister [[Sardar Usman Buzdar]] and was appointed as Minister for Irrigation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab\u2019s 23-member cabinet sworn in |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/08/27/punjabs-23-member-cabinet-sworn-in/ |accessdate=28 August 2018 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk |date=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan Leghari, Muhammad Mohsin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani senators (14th Parliament)]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Punjab MPAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Punjab MPAs 2008\u20132013]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Punjab)]]\n[[Category:Provincial ministers of Punjab]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_Mohsin_Khan_Leghari"}
{"title_page": "Fetch the Bolt Cutters", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = A black-and-white close-up of Apple with a very thick black border that has hand-drawn lightning bolts on either side and the artist and title written in a hand-drawn purple font\n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = July 2015&nbsp;\u2013 March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house (Los Angeles)\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please do not add genres without a reliable source -->\n| length       = 51:54\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, Apple's first release since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012. Apple began recording the album in 2015, producing and performing it alongside Amy Aileen Wood, [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]. It features a percussive sound, and lyrically explores \"not being afraid to speak\".  The album received universal critical acclaim upon its release, becoming the first album in review aggregator [[Metacritic]]'s history to receive a weighted average score of 100 upon its initial release.\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah.\n\nIn February 2015, she began rehearsals for the album with band members [[Sebastian Steinberg]], Amy Aileen Wood and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"VultureProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Allow Fiona Apple to Reintroduce Herself|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> They began writing and rehearsing in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting as they marched around the house.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July, they began recording the album, spending three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. A few months later, after returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=[[NME]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe album's sound is percussive and raw. Songs feature looped sections, and sudden tempo changes. Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\". Lyrically, Apple identified its main theme as \"not being afraid to speak\". She also explores her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile. The title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> The next month, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| AOTY = 95/100<ref name=\"aoty\">{{cite web |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters - Reviews |url=https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/224348-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.php |publisher=Album of The Year |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| ADM = 9.1/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Fetch The Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple reviews|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11368/Fiona-Apple-Fetch-The-Bolt-Cutters.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 100/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev1score = A<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/with-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-fiona-apple-hits-a-zenith-1842908893|title=With Fetch The Bolt Cutters, Fiona Apple hits a zenith of liberation and experimentation|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/17/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a glorious eruption|last=Barton|first=Laura|author-link=Laura Barton|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Irish Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-a-bracing-collection-1.4228651|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 A bracing collection|last=Clayton-Lea|first=Tony|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-2648715|title=Fiona Apple \u2013 \u2018Fetch The Bolt Cutters\u2019 review: an intoxicating listen that will cut deep|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[NME]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/18/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-fourth-album-strange-exceptional|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a strange, exceptional record|last=Empire|first=Kitty|author-link=Kitty Empire|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[The Observer]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-2-984926/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019 Is a Triumphant Statement of Self-Discovery and Solidarity\n|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev9score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' was met with widespread acclaim, with many critics deeming it an instant classic, a masterpiece, and Apple's best work to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-roundup.html|title=Critics Agree: Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is an Instant Classic|last=Curto|first=Justin|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> At review aggregator [[Metacritic]], the release received a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 100 out of 100, based on 17 reviews,<ref name=\"MC\" /> making it the highest-rated non-retrospective album in the website's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/albums/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc|title=Best Music and Albums of All Time|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also the second highest-rated album on review aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]], with a rating of 9.1/10.<ref name=\"adm\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' in 2010, with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/fiona-apples-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-scores-a-10-on-pitchfork/ |title=Pitchfork gives Fiona Apple's new album a 10 |last=Hatfield |first=Amanda |date=April 17, 2020 |website=[[BrooklynVegan]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pitchfork-fiona-apple-first-perfect-score-decade/ |title=Pitchfork just gave Fiona Apple their first perfect score in almost a decade |last=Jenke |first=Brittany |date=April 17, 2020 |website=Tone Deaf |publisher=The Brag |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> [[Laura Barton]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on the album's \"refusal to be silenced\", writing: \"The result is that this seems not so much an album as a sudden glorious eruption; after eight long years, an urgent desire to be heard\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here\u2014a rich text to scour\", adding \"you'd need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s stunningly intimate new album makes a bold show of unprettiness|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly praised the album for its \"conversational tone, manifested in Apple\u2019s talky delivery as well as in lyrics that scan as prose more often than poetry, [which] creates a rare intimacy\", and commented that \"As beautiful as the melodies and the epiphanies they carry often are, the songs are not what you would call \u2018pretty.\u2019...Yet ''Bolt Cutters''\u00a0wouldn\u2019t be the extraordinary experiment in aural and lyrical honesty that it is if it sounded too polished\".<ref name=\"Time Magazine\">{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5823031/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is Raw, Introspective and Everything We Need Out of a Fiona Apple Album|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Maura Johnston]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' applauded the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality\", and added that \"even [during] the most intense moments of ''Fetch,'' her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" She also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]]\", which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref name=\"Boston Globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple makes defiance sound exhilarating on \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019|last=Johnston|first=Maura|author-link=Maura Johnston|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Boston Globe]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'''s [[Kitty Empire]] described the album as \"a strange and exceptional record, even within the context of an uncommon career\".<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage\", describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/|title=Album review: Fiona Apple's 'Fetch the Bolt Cutters' is a blistering, emotional triumph|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:59\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 9, 10)}}, [[Casio]] drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background vocals {{small|(2\u20135, 7\u201313)}}, drums {{small|(3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, metal butterfly {{small|(3)}}, [[Mellotron]] {{small|(6, 12)}}, electronic drums {{small|(7)}}, timpani {{small|(7)}}, [[Wurlitzer electric piano|Wurlitzer]] {{small|(8)}}, Casio {{small|(9)}}, bells {{small|(9)}}, chair {{small|(12)}}\n* [[Sebastian Steinberg]] \u2013\u00a0bass {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 5, 9)}}, [[Autoharp#Electric autoharp|electric autoharp]] {{small|(10, 13)}}, acoustic 12-string guitar {{small|(10)}}, slide guitar {{small|(10)}}, background vocals {{small|(12)}}, lighter on Wurlitzer {{small|(12)}}, harp {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}, stomps {{small|(13)}}, breathing {{small|(13)}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013 drums {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 4, 5, 9, 10, 13)}}, loops {{small|(10)}}\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]] \u2013\u00a0[[vibraphone|vibes]] {{small|(4, 8)}}, percussion {{small|(5, 8, 9, 12, 13)}}, guitar {{small|(6, 7)}}, background vocals {{small|(8, 12)}}, Mellotron {{small|(8)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}, Wurlitzer {{small|(10)}}, organ {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n{{div col}}\n* [[Best Coast|Bobb Bruno]] \u2013\u00a0special effects {{small|(2, 5)}}\n* [[Cara Delevingne]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(3)}}\n* Mercy \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}, collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* Maddie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Leo \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Alfie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* [[John Would]] \u2013\u00a0Wurlitzer {{small|(4)}}, organ {{small|(4)}}, piano {{small|(8)}}\n* Little \u2013\u00a0collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* [[Maude Maggart]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7, 8)}}\n* Winifred Lucky \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7)}}\n* Spencer Maggart \u2013\u00a0soft shoe stomp {{small|(13)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Engineers'''\n{{div col}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u201310, 13)}}\n* John Would \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u20135, 8\u201310, 12, 13)}}, mixing {{small|(8)}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(5\u20137, 9\u201311, 13)}}\n* [[Dave Way]] \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|1719775}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|a9ee533f-8871-4f62-a6bb-91eb264abc90}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sebastian Steinberg]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = A black-and-white close-up of Apple with a very thick black border that has hand-drawn lightning bolts on either side and the artist and title written in a hand-drawn purple font\n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = July 2015&nbsp;\u2013 March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house (Los Angeles)\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please do not add genres without a reliable source -->\n| length       = 51:54\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, Apple's first release since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012. Apple began recording the album in 2015, producing and performing it alongside Amy Aileen Wood, [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]. It features a percussive sound, and lyrically explores \"not being afraid to speak\".  The album received universal critical acclaim upon its release, becoming the first album in review aggregator [[Metacritic]]'s history to receive a weighted average score of 100 upon its initial release.\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah.\n\nIn February 2015, she began rehearsals for the album with band members [[Sebastian Steinberg]], Amy Aileen Wood and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"VultureProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Allow Fiona Apple to Reintroduce Herself|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> They began writing and rehearsing in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting as they marched around the house.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July, they began recording the album, spending three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. A few months later, after returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=[[NME]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe album's sound is percussive and raw. Songs feature looped sections, and sudden tempo changes. Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\". Lyrically, Apple identified its main theme as \"not being afraid to speak\". She also explores her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile. The title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> The next month, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| AOTY = 95/100<ref name=\"aoty\">{{cite web |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters - Reviews |url=https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/224348-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.php |publisher=Album of The Year |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| ADM = 9.1/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Fetch The Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple reviews|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11368/Fiona-Apple-Fetch-The-Bolt-Cutters.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 100/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev1score = A<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/with-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-fiona-apple-hits-a-zenith-1842908893|title=With Fetch The Bolt Cutters, Fiona Apple hits a zenith of liberation and experimentation|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/17/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a glorious eruption|last=Barton|first=Laura|author-link=Laura Barton|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Irish Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-a-bracing-collection-1.4228651|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 A bracing collection|last=Clayton-Lea|first=Tony|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-2648715|title=Fiona Apple \u2013 \u2018Fetch The Bolt Cutters\u2019 review: an intoxicating listen that will cut deep|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[NME]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/18/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-fourth-album-strange-exceptional|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a strange, exceptional record|last=Empire|first=Kitty|author-link=Kitty Empire|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[The Observer]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-2-984926/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019 Is a Triumphant Statement of Self-Discovery and Solidarity\n|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev9score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' was met with widespread acclaim, with many critics deeming it an instant classic, a masterpiece, and Apple's best work to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-roundup.html|title=Critics Agree: Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is an Instant Classic|last=Curto|first=Justin|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> At review aggregator [[Metacritic]], the release received a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 100 out of 100, based on 17 reviews,<ref name=\"MC\" /> making it the highest-rated new album in the website's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/albums/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc|title=Best Music and Albums of All Time|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also the second highest-rated album on review aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]], with a rating of 9.1/10.<ref name=\"adm\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' in 2010, with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/fiona-apples-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-scores-a-10-on-pitchfork/ |title=Pitchfork gives Fiona Apple's new album a 10 |last=Hatfield |first=Amanda |date=April 17, 2020 |website=[[BrooklynVegan]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pitchfork-fiona-apple-first-perfect-score-decade/ |title=Pitchfork just gave Fiona Apple their first perfect score in almost a decade |last=Jenke |first=Brittany |date=April 17, 2020 |website=Tone Deaf |publisher=The Brag |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> [[Laura Barton]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on the album's \"refusal to be silenced\", writing: \"The result is that this seems not so much an album as a sudden glorious eruption; after eight long years, an urgent desire to be heard\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here\u2014a rich text to scour\", adding \"you'd need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s stunningly intimate new album makes a bold show of unprettiness|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly praised the album for its \"conversational tone, manifested in Apple\u2019s talky delivery as well as in lyrics that scan as prose more often than poetry, [which] creates a rare intimacy\", and commented that \"As beautiful as the melodies and the epiphanies they carry often are, the songs are not what you would call \u2018pretty.\u2019...Yet ''Bolt Cutters''\u00a0wouldn\u2019t be the extraordinary experiment in aural and lyrical honesty that it is if it sounded too polished\".<ref name=\"Time Magazine\">{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5823031/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is Raw, Introspective and Everything We Need Out of a Fiona Apple Album|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Maura Johnston]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' applauded the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality\", and added that \"even [during] the most intense moments of ''Fetch,'' her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" She also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]]\", which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref name=\"Boston Globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple makes defiance sound exhilarating on \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019|last=Johnston|first=Maura|author-link=Maura Johnston|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Boston Globe]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'''s [[Kitty Empire]] described the album as \"a strange and exceptional record, even within the context of an uncommon career\".<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage\", describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/|title=Album review: Fiona Apple's 'Fetch the Bolt Cutters' is a blistering, emotional triumph|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:59\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 9, 10)}}, [[Casio]] drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background vocals {{small|(2\u20135, 7\u201313)}}, drums {{small|(3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, metal butterfly {{small|(3)}}, [[Mellotron]] {{small|(6, 12)}}, electronic drums {{small|(7)}}, timpani {{s