rcraft_16-19.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-08|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=8 March 2012|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n|ferry range km=\n|ferry range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=25000\n|ceiling note=<big>+</big><ref>{{cite web|url=http://csef.ru/en/oborona-i-bezopasnost/423/boj-v-blizhnem-kosmose-na-kakih-vysotah-sposoben-voevat-rossijskij-mig-31-7462|title=The combat in middle space: at what altitude are able to fight the Russian MiG-31|website=csef.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004190117/http://csef.ru/en/oborona-i-bezopasnost/423/boj-v-blizhnem-kosmose-na-kakih-vysotah-sposoben-voevat-rossijskij-mig-31-7462|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|g limits=<big>+</big>5\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|climb rate ms=288\n|climb rate note=\n|time to altitude=\n|wing loading kg/m2=665\n|wing loading note=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|thrust/weight=0.85\n\n|more performance=\n<!--\n        Armament\n-->\n|guns=1 \u00d7 [[23\u00d7115mm|23 mm]] [[Gryazev-Shipunov GSh-6-23]]M [[rotary cannon]] with 800 rounds (later removed)\n|hardpoints=8 \u00d7 underwing pylons\n|hardpoint missiles=\n[[Air-to-air missile]]s:\n**4 \u00d7 [[R-33 (missile)|R-33]]E\n**4 \u00d7 [[R-60 (missile)|R-60]]MK\n**2 \u00d7 [[R-40 (missile)|R-40]]RD/TD\n*[[Air-to-surface missile]]s:\n**4 \u00d7 [[Kh-58]]UShKE [[anti-radiation missile]]\n**1 \u00d7 [[Kh-47M2 Kinzhal]] hypersonic [[air-launched ballistic missile]]\n<!--\n     Avionics -->\n|avionics=\n*8TK [[Infrared_search_and_track|IRST]]<ref>\"MiG-31 d\u00e1le rozv\u00edjen - MagnetPress\". www.vydavatelstvo-mps.sk.</ref>\n*[[Phazotron]] [[Zaslon]] [[passive electronically scanned array]] [[radar]]\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n{{aircontent\n|see also=<!-- other related articles that have not already linked: -->\n* [[Firefox (novel)|''Firefox'' (novel)]] and [[Firefox (film)|''Firefox'' (film)]], the premise of which is the theft of a speculated/fictional version of the MiG-31\n|related=<!-- designs which were developed into or from this aircraft: -->\n* [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25]]\n* [[Mikoyan MiG-41]]\n|similar aircraft=<!-- aircraft that are of similar role, era, and capability as this design: -->\n* [[Grumman F-14 Tomcat]]\n* [[McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle]]\n* [[Panavia Tornado ADV]]\n* [[Sukhoi Su-27]]\n|lists=<!-- relevant lists that this aircraft appears in: -->\n* [[List of military aircraft of the Soviet Union and the CIS]]\n<!-- See [[WP:Air/PC]] for more explanation of these fields. -->\n}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Crickmore, Paul F. [https://books.google.com/books?id=xwPFC3GtcL8C&printsec=frontcover ''Lockheed Blackbird: Beyond the Secret Missions''.] Oxford, UK: Osprey Publishing, 2004. {{ISBN|1-84176-694-1}}.\n* Eden, Paul, ed. \"Mikoyan MiG-25 'Foxbat'\". \"Mikoyan MiG-31 'Foxhound'\". ''Encyclopedia of Modern Military Aircraft''. London: Amber Books, 2004. {{ISBN|1-904687-84-9}}.\n* Gordon, Yefim. ''MiG-25 'Foxbat,' MiG-31 'Foxhound:\" Russia's Defensive Front Line''. Hinckley, UK: Midland Publishing, 1997. {{ISBN|1-85780-064-8}}.\n* Spick, Mike. \"MiG-31 'Foxhound'\". ''The Great Book of Modern Warplanes''. St. Paul, Minnesota: MBI, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7603-0893-4}}.\n* Wilson, Stewart. ''Combat Aircraft since 1945''. Fyshwick, Australia: Aerospace Publications, 2000. {{ISBN|1-875671-50-1}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080107063714/http://www.migavia.ru/eng/military_e/MiG_31_E_e.htm MiG-31E page on Russian Aircraft Corporation \"MiG\" site]\n*[http://www.milavia.net/aircraft/mig-31/mig-31.htm MiG-31 page on milavia.net]\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/russia/mig-31.htm MiG-31 Foxhound at Global Security]\n\n{{Mikoyan aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:Mikoyan aircraft|MiG-031]]\n[[Category:1970s Soviet fighter aircraft]]\n[[Category:Twinjets]]\n[[Category:Shoulder-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 1975]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interceptor aircraft}}\n{{Hatnote|For the fictional aircraft of the novel and movie [[Firefox (film)|''Firefox'']], see [[List of fictional aircraft]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout, and guidelines. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = MiG-31\n| image = File:Russian Air Force MiG-31 inflight Pichugin.jpg <!-- In-flight images are preferred for aircraft. Discuss possible changes on talk page before changing. -->\n| caption = Russian Air Force MiG-31B in 2011\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Interceptor aircraft]], [[attack aircraft]]<!-- for MiG-31K with Kinzhal missile; this needs to be stated in article text & sourced.-->\n| national origin = Soviet Union\n| manufacturer = [[Russian Aircraft Corporation MiG|Mikoyan-Gurevich/Mikoyan]]\n| first flight = 16 September 1975\n| introduced = 6 May 1981\n| retired = \n| status = In service\n| primary user = [[Russian Aerospace Forces]]\n| more users = [[Kazakhstan Air Force]]\n| produced = 1975\u20131994\n| number built = 519<ref name=Mladenov>{{cite journal |last1=Mladenov |first1=Alexander |title=The Foxhound's New Tricks |journal=Air International |date=July 2015 |volume=19 |issue=1|page=28}}</ref>\n| unit cost = \n| developed from = [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25]]\n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Mikoyan MiG-31''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0438\u043a\u043e\u044f\u043d \u041c\u0438\u0413-31}}; [[NATO reporting name]]: '''Foxhound''') is a supersonic [[interceptor aircraft]] developed for use by the [[Soviet Air Forces]]. The aircraft was designed by the [[Mikoyan]] design bureau as a replacement for the earlier [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25|MiG-25 \"Foxbat\"]]; the MiG-31 is based on and shares design elements with the MiG-25.<ref name=\"Great Book\" /> The MiG-31 has the distinction of being among the fastest combat jets in the world.{{cn|date=February 2020}} It continues to be operated by the [[Russian Air Force]] and the [[Armed Forces of the Republic of Kazakhstan|Kazakhstan Air Force]] following the end of the [[Cold War]] and the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|collapse of the Soviet Union]] in 1991. The Russian Defence Ministry expects the MiG-31 to remain in service until 2030 or beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/business/article/russias-modernized-soviet-era-mig-31-fighters-to-fly-for-50-years/518895.html|title=Russia's Modernized Soviet-Era MiG-31 Fighters to Fly for 50 Years|date=April 9, 2015|publisher=[[The Moscow Times]]|access-date=5 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413005601/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/business/article/russias-modernized-soviet-era-mig-31-fighters-to-fly-for-50-years/518895.html|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== Origins ===\nThe MiG-25 underwent substantial design sacrifices in order to achieve high speed, altitude and rate of climb. However, it lacked maneuverability at interception speeds and was difficult to fly at low altitudes. The MiG-25's speed was limited to [[Mach number|Mach]] 2.83, but it could reach a maximum speed of Mach 3.2 or more with the risk of engine damage.<ref name=\"Dawes\" /><ref>Gunston and Spick 1983, pp. 132\u2013133.</ref>\n\n[[File:Russian Air Force Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31BM Pichugin-1.jpg|thumb|left|MiG-31BM taking off from [[Chelyabinsk Shagol Airport]] in 2012]]\nDevelopment of the MiG-25's replacement began with the Ye-155MP ({{lang-ru|\u0415-155\u041c\u041f}}) [[prototype]] which first flew on 16 September 1975.<ref name=Eden_p323>Eden 2004, p. 323.</ref>  Although it bore a superficial resemblance to the MiG-25, it had a longer fuselage to accommodate the radar operator's cockpit and was in many respects a new design. An important development was the MiG-31's advanced radar, capable of both look-up and [[look-down/shoot-down]] engagement, as well as multiple target tracking. This gave the Soviet Union an interceptor with the capability to engage the most likely Western intruders (low flying cruise missiles and bombers) at long range.{{cn|date=February 2020}} The MiG-31 replaced the [[Tu-128]] as the Soviet Union's dedicated long-range interceptor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airbase.ru/sb/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/index-t.htm|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31|website=www.airbase.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|lang=ru|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723223444/http://www.airbase.ru/sb/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/index-t.htm|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with far more advanced sensors and weapons,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/russias-super-sized-tu-128-fighter-the-supersonic-b-52-19972|title=Russia's Super-Sized Tu-128 Fighter: The Supersonic B-52 Killer|first=Sebastien|last=Roblin|date=1 April 2017|website=The National Interest|accessdate=2 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128191037/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/russias-super-sized-tu-128-fighter-the-supersonic-b-52-19972|archive-date=28 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> while its range is almost double that of the MiG-25.\n\nLike its MiG-25 predecessor, the introduction of the MiG-31 was surrounded by early speculation and misinformation concerning its design and abilities. The West learned of the new interceptor from Lieutenant [[Viktor Belenko]], a pilot who defected to [[Japan]] in 1976 with his MiG-25P.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eyster, II|first1=James P.|title=The Defection of Viktor Belenko: The Use of International Law to Justify Political Decisions|journal=Fordham International Law Journal|date=1977|volume=1|issue=1|url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=ilj|accessdate=30 October 2015|publisher=The Berkeley Electronic Press (bepress)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709164851/http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=ilj|archive-date=9 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Belenko described an upcoming \"Super Foxbat\" with two seats and an ability to intercept cruise missiles. According to his testimony, the new interceptor was to have air intakes similar to the [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-23]], which the MiG-31 does not have, at least in production variants.<ref>{{cite web|title=MiG-31 Foxhound|url=http://www.globalaircraft.org/planes/mig-31_foxhound.pl|website=Global Aircraft|publisher=The Global Aircraft Organization|accessdate=30 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009212732/http://www.globalaircraft.org/planes/mig-31_foxhound.pl|archive-date=9 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Into production ===\nSerial production of the MiG-31 began in 1979.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arms-expo.ru/news/armed_forces/mig_31_moderniziruetsya_i_prosluzhit_v_vvs_rossii_eshche_okolo_15_let/?sphrase_id=2636609|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u0432 \u0412\u0412\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0435\u0449\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e 15 \u043b\u0435\u0442|work=arms-expo.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018135417/http://www.arms-expo.ru/news/armed_forces/mig_31_moderniziruetsya_i_prosluzhit_v_vvs_rossii_eshche_okolo_15_let/?sphrase_id=2636609|archive-date=18 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.ru/politika/1369019|title=\u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d: \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u0435\u0449\u0435 15 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0412\u0412\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|access-date=9 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006121428/http://tass.ru/politika/1369019|archive-date=6 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The MiG-31 is able to maintain combat effectiveness despite the potential use of active and passive radar jammers and thermal decoys by adversaries. A group of four MiG-31 interceptors is able to control an area of air space across a total length of {{convert|800|to|900|km|mi}};<ref name=\"aviationweek.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/uploads/2014/10/1991-%20MiG-31%20At%20Le%20Bourget.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509055528/https://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/uploads/2014/10/1991-%20MiG-31%20At%20Le%20Bourget.pdf |archive-date=9 May 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> its radar possessing a maximum detection range of {{convert|200|km|mi|sigfig=2}} in distance (radius) and the typical width of detection along the front of {{convert|225|km|mi|sigfig=2}}.<ref name=\"arms-expo.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arms-expo.ru/049049056052124051050056051%2Ehtml |accessdate=19 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214070309/http://www.arms-expo.ru/049049056052124051050056051.html |archivedate=14 December 2013|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31, (Foxhound), \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0445\u0437\u0432\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c|lang=ru}}</ref>\n\nThe MiG-31 was designed to fulfill the following mission objectives:<ref name=Mladenov />\n*Intercept cruise missiles and their launch aircraft by reaching missile launch range in the lowest possible time after departing the loiter area;\n*Detect and destroy low flying cruise missiles, UAVs and helicopters;\n*Long range escort of strategic bombers;\n*Provide strategic air defense in areas not covered by ground-based, air defense systems.\n\nMiG-31 production ended in 1994.<ref name=\"encyclopaedia-russia.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopaedia-russia.ru/article.php?id=599|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31|work=encyclopaedia-russia.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129011632/http://www.encyclopaedia-russia.ru/article.php?id=599|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first production batch of 519 MiG-31s including 349 \"baseline models\" was produced at the Sokol plant between 1976 and 1988.  The second batch of 101 MiG-31DZs was produced from 1989 to 1991. The final batch of 69 MiG-31B aircraft was produced between 1990 and 1994. From the final batch 50 were retained by the Kazakhstan Air Force after the dissolution of the Soviet Union. Of the \"baseline models\", 40 airframes were upgraded to MiG-31BS standard.<ref name=Mladenov />\n\n=== Upgrades and replacement ===\nSome upgrade programs have found their way into the MiG-31 fleet, like the MiG-31BM multirole version with upgraded avionics, new multimode radar, hands-on-throttle-and-stick ([[HOTAS]]) controls, [[liquid crystal display|liquid crystal]] (LCD) color multi-function displays (MFDs), ability to carry the [[R-77]] missile and various Russian [[air-to-surface missile|air-to-ground missiles]] (AGMs) such as the [[Kh-31]] [[anti-radiation missile]] (ARM), a new and more powerful computer, and digital [[data link]]s. A project to upgrade the Russian MiG-31 fleet to the MiG-31BM standard began in 2010;<ref name=RIAN_completing_MiG-31BM>Skrynnikov, R. [http://en.rian.ru/mlitary_news/20100813/160190708.html \"Defense: Russian air force completing MiG-31BM modernization program.\"] ''RIA Novosti'', 13 August 2010. Retrieved: 17 August 2010. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816041955/http://en.rian.ru/mlitary_news/20100813/160190708.html |date=16 August 2010 }}</ref> 100 aircraft are to be upgraded to MiG-31BM standard by 2020.<ref>Ankov, Vitaliy. [http://en.rian.ru/military_news/20120102/170592615.html \"Russia to modernize 60 MiG-31 interceptors by 2020.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609022721/http://en.rian.ru/military_news/20120102/170592615.html |date=9 June 2013 }} ''RIA Novosti'', 2 January 2012. Retrieved: 25 November 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2014/1127/165026811/detail.shtml|title=\u0426\u0410\u041c\u0422\u041e / \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 / \u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u041e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31|date=27 November 2014|work=armstrade.org|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209202756/http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2014/1127/165026811/detail.shtml|archive-date=9 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Russian Federation Defence Ministry chief Colonel Yuri Balyko has claimed that the upgrade will increase the combat effectiveness of the aircraft several times over.<ref>[http://www.royfc.com/acft_news_old_nov2.html \"MiG-31 Upgrade Will Quadruple Its Effectiveness \u2013 Expert.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221035501/http://www.royfc.com/acft_news_old_nov2.html |date=21 February 2009 }} ''royfc.com.'' Retrieved: 24 January 2011.</ref> 18 MIG-31BMs were delivered in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itar-tass.com/armiya-i-opk/1660936|title=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421: \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u041e\u041f\u041a \u2013 \u0428\u043e\u0439\u0433\u0443: \u043e\u0441\u043d\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0438 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0434 \u0432\u044b\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 7%|work=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230084808/http://itar-tass.com/armiya-i-opk/1660936|archive-date=30 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Russian military will receive more than 130 upgraded MiG-31BMs, and the first 24 aircraft have already been delivered, Russian Deputy Defense Minister Yuri Borisov told reporters on 9 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2015/0409/152528676/detail.shtml|title=\u0426\u0410\u041c\u0422\u041e / \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 / \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0435 24 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0412\u0421 \u0420\u0424|website=www.armstrade.org|access-date=10 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414054519/http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2015/0409/152528676/detail.shtml|archive-date=14 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRussia plans to start development of a replacement for the MiG-31 by 2019. The aircraft will be called PAK-DP (\u041f\u0410\u041a \u0414\u041f, ''\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430'' \u2013 Prospective Air Complex for Long-Range Interception).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/53633/russia-to-launch-mig-31-replacement-programme-before-end-of-decade |title=Russia to launch MiG-31 replacement programme before end of decade|last=Jennings|first=Gareth|access-date=8 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072342/http://www.janes.com/article/53633/russia-to-launch-mig-31-replacement-programme-before-end-of-decade |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Development of the new aircraft, designated [[Mikoyan MiG-41|MiG-41]], began in April 2013.  Such development is favored over restarting MiG-31 production.<ref name=\"replace\">[http://en.rian.ru/military_news/20130411/180584483/Russia-to-Field-MiG-31-Replacement-by-2020---Commander.html \"Russia to Field MiG-31 Replacement by 2020\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414062354/http://en.rian.ru/military_news/20130411/180584483/Russia-to-Field-MiG-31-Replacement-by-2020---Commander.html |date=14 April 2013 }}. RIA Novosti, 11 April 2013.</ref> In March 2014, Russian test pilot [[Anatoly Kvochur]] said that work began on a Mach 4 capable MiG-41 based on the MiG-31.<ref>[http://theaviationist.com/2014/03/05/mig-41-mig-31-replacement/ \"The Russian Armed Forces are working on the Mig-41, a new supersonic fighter based on the Mig-31 Foxhound.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305165157/http://theaviationist.com/2014/03/05/mig-41-mig-31-replacement/ |date=5 March 2014 }} theaviationist.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.migflug.com/jetflights/mig-41-a-new-mach-4-fighter.html|title=MiG-41 \u2013 Mikoyan is developing a new, faster Mach 4+ interceptor. \u00bb MiGFlug.com Blog|website=www.migflug.com|access-date=30 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053425/http://www.migflug.com/jetflights/mig-41-a-new-mach-4-fighter.html|archive-date=8 August 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Later reports said that development of the MiG-31 replacement is to begin in 2017, with the first aircraft to be delivered in 2020, and the replacement entering service in 2025.<ref>[http://en.ria.ru/military_news/20140811/191909247/Russia-to-Start-Developing-Replacement-for-MiG-31-in-2017.html \"Russia to Start Developing Replacement for MiG-31 in 2017\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812205111/http://en.ria.ru/military_news/20140811/191909247/Russia-to-Start-Developing-Replacement-for-MiG-31-in-2017.html |date=12 August 2014 }}. RIA Novosti, 11 August 2014.</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Overview ===\n[[File:Russian Air Force Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31 Pichugin-1.jpg|thumb|A MiG-31DZ in flight over Russia, 2012]]\n\nLike the MiG-25, the MiG-31 is a large twin-engine aircraft with side-mounted air [[intake ramp]]s, a shoulder-mounted wing with an [[aspect ratio (wing)|aspect ratio]] of 2.94, and twin vertical tailfins. Unlike the MiG-25, it has two seats, with the rear occupied by a dedicated [[weapon systems officer]].<ref name=\"sr-71-vs\">{{cite web|url=http://theaviationist.com/2013/12/11/sr-71-vs-mig-31/|title=How the Mig-31 repelled the SR-71 Blackbird from Soviet skies|work=theaviationist.com|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419161248/http://theaviationist.com/2013/12/11/sr-71-vs-mig-31/|archive-date=19 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The MiG-31 is limited to five&nbsp;[[g-force|''g'']] when travelling at supersonic speeds.<ref name=\"Dawes\" /> While flying under combat weight, its [[wing loading]] is marginal and its [[thrust-to-weight ratio]] is favorable. The MiG-31 is not designed for [[dogfight|close combat or rapid turning]].<ref name=\"Dawes\">Dawes, Alan. \"Mikoyan's Long-Legged Hunting Dog.\" ''Air International,'' December 2002, pp. 396\u2013401.</ref>\n\nThe wings and airframe of the MiG-31 are stronger than those of the MiG-25, permitting supersonic flight at low altitudes. Like the MiG-25, its flight surfaces are built primarily of nickel-steel alloy, enabling the aircraft to tolerate [[Aerodynamic heating|kinetic heating]] at airspeeds approaching Mach 3. The MiG-31 airframe comprises 49% arc-welded nickel steel, 33% light metal alloy, 16% titanium and 2% composites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aircraftinformation.info/art_mig31.htm|title=The MiG-31 Foxhound: One of the World's Greatest Interceptors|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903060533/http://www.aircraftinformation.info/art_mig31.htm|archive-date=3 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its [[Aviadvigatel D30-F6|D30-F6]] jet engines, each rated at 152&nbsp;kN thrust, allow a maximum speed of [[Mach number|Mach]] 1.23 at low altitude. High-altitude speed is temperature-redlined to Mach 2.83 \u2013 the thrust-to-drag ratio is sufficient for speeds in excess of Mach 3, but such speeds pose unacceptable hazards to engine and airframe life in routine use.<ref name=\"Dawes\" />\n\n=== Electronics suite ===\n[[File:DN-ST-92-02246.JPEG|thumb|MiG-31BM showing its ''Zaslon'' phased-array radar]]\n\nThe MiG-31 was among the first aircraft with a [[phased array radar]], and one of two aircraft in the world capable of independently firing long-range [[air-to-air missile]]s as of 2013.<ref name=\"ria.ru\">{{cite web |url=http://ria.ru/incidents/20131214/984063920.html |title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31. \u041b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438 |work=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018035211/http://ria.ru/incidents/20131214/984063920.html |archive-date=18 October 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://fun-space.ru/aviacziya/2149-mig-31|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u2013 FUN-SPACE.ru|first=Super|last=User|website=fun-space.ru|access-date=14 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117152609/http://fun-space.ru/aviacziya/2149-mig-31|archive-date=17 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralay.com/mig31m.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31|work=paralay.com|accessdate=6 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222125931/http://paralay.com/mig31m.html|archivedate=22 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last1=Cenciotti |first1=David |title=Iranian F-14 Tomcat\u2019s \"new\" indigenous air-to-air missile is actually an (improved?) AIM-54 Phoenix replica |url=http://theaviationist.com/2013/09/26/farouk-missile/ |website=The Aviationist |publisher=David Cenciotti |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=24 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923070412/http://theaviationist.com/2013/09/26/farouk-missile/ |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |last1=Nassirkhani |first1=Major Farhad |title=The first and only country to receive F-14 Tomcat was, The Nirouyeh Havaiyeh Shahanshahiye Iran, or Imperial Iranian Air Force |url=http://www.iiaf.net/aircraft/jetfighters/F14/f14.html |website=ImperialIranianAirForce.net |publisher=Fred Nassirkhani |location= Rancho Santa Margarita, CA |accessdate=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924033338/http://www.iiaf.net/aircraft/jetfighters/F14/f14.html |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe MiG-31 was the world's first operational fighter with a [[passive electronically scanned array]] radar (PESA), the ''[[Zaslon radar|Zaslon S-800]]''. Its maximum range against fighter-sized targets is approximately 200&nbsp;km, and it can track up to 10 targets and simultaneously attack four of them with its [[Vympel NPO|Vympel]] [[R-33 (missile)|R-33]] missiles. The radar is matched with an [[infra-red search and track]] (IRST) system in a retractable undernose fairing.<ref name=\"Dawes\" />\n\nThe MiG-31 was equipped with RK-RLDN and APD-518<ref name=\"airwar.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31|work=airwar.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316120226/http://airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31.html|archive-date=16 March 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> digital secure datalinks. The RK-RLDN datalink is for communication with ground control centers. The APD-518 datalink enables a flight of four MiG-31 to automatically exchange radar-generated data within 200&nbsp;km from each other. It also enables other aircraft with less sophisticated avionics,<ref name=\"\u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438.\u0440\u0444\">http://\u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438.\u0440\u0444/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/bm/mig31bm.htm {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420112113/http://xn--80akhcovnjb1g.xn--p1ai/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/bm/mig31bm.htm |date=20 April 2017 }}</ref> such as MiG-23,25,29/Su-15,27<ref name=\"arms-expo.ru\" /> to be directed to targets spotted by MiG-31 (a maximum of four (long-range) for each MiG-31 aircraft). The [[Beriev A-50|A-50]] [[airborne early warning|AEW]] aircraft and MiG-31 can automatically exchange aerial and terrestrial radar target designation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vpk-news.ru/articles/15752|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31: \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u044b|work=vpk-news.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221130337/http://vpk-news.ru/articles/15752|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as well as air defense.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://rg.ru/2014/02/03/mig-site.html|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31|website=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|access-date=26 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026231757/https://rg.ru/2014/02/03/mig-site.html|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The MiG-31 is equipped with ECM of radar and infrared ranges,<ref name=\"worldweapon.ru\" /> and is capable of performing combat tasks.\n\nThe flight-navigation equipment of the MiG-31 includes a complex of automatic control system SAU-155\u041cP and sighting-navigation complex KN-25 with two inertial systems and IP-1-72A with digital computer, electronic long range navigation system Radical NP (312) or A-331, electronic system of the long-range [[navigation]] A-723. Distant radio navigation is carried out by means of two systems: [[CHAYKA|Chayka]] (similar to the system of [[LORAN|Loran]]) and \u00abRoute\u00bb (similar to the system of Omega).{{clarify|date=February 2014}}\n\nSimilarly to the complex [[S-300 missile system]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://3mv.ru/publ/aviacija_nato_protiv_sirijskikh_s_300/1-1-0-16489|title=\u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041d\u0410\u0422\u041e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0441\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421-300|work=3mv.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004135821/http://3mv.ru/publ/aviacija_nato_protiv_sirijskikh_s_300/1-1-0-16489|archive-date=4 October 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> aircraft group with APD-518 can: share data obtained by various radars from different directions (active or passive scanning of radiation) and summarize the data. The target can be detected passively (through noise posed to protect themselves / active search radar (target)) and (or) actively simultaneously from many different directions (active search radar of MiG-31). Every aircraft with the APD-518 will have the exact data, even if it is not involved in the search.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"airwar.ru\" /><ref name=\"milrus.com\" />\n* interacting with ground-based automated digital control system (ACS \u00abRubezh\u00bb Operating radius of {{convert|2000|km|mi}}, can control multiple groups of planes), operating modes of remote aiming, semi-automated actions (coordinate support), singly, and also: to direct on the target missiles launched from the other aircraft.\n* Digital immune system provides the automatic exchange of tactical information in a group of four interceptors, remote one from another at a distance of 200&nbsp;km and aiming at the target group of fighters with less-powerful avionics (in this case the aircraft performs the role of guidance point or repeater).<ref name=\"arms-expo.ru\" />\n\n=== Radars ===\nAdopted in 1981 RP-31 N007 ''backstop'' (Russian: ''Zaslon'').<ref name=\"milrus.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milrus.com/vvs/mig31/text.shtml|title=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f. \u0418\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31. \u0412\u0422\u0420|work=milrus.com|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314135252/http://www.milrus.com/vvs/mig31/text.shtml|archive-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* the range of detection of air targets with Zaslon-A: 200&nbsp;km (for the purpose of a [[radar cross-section]] of 19&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup> on a collision angle with probability 0.5)\n* target detection distance with [[radar cross-section]] of 3&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup> in the rear within 35&nbsp;km with a probability of 0.5<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.niip.ru/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12:-l-r-lr&catid=8:2011-07-06-06-33-26&Itemid=8|title=\u0421\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0421\u0423\u0412 \"\u0417\u0430\u0441\u043b\u043e\u043d\" \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0413-31|author=\u0421\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0418\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430|work=niip.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627005204/https://www.niip.ru/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12:-l-r-lr&catid=8:2011-07-06-06-33-26&Itemid=8|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>http://www.roe.ru/cataloque/air_craft/aircraft_16-19.pdf{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* number of detected targets: 24 (was originally 10<ref name=\"militaryparitet.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.militaryparitet.com/vp/65/|title=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0443. \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 F-14 \u2013 \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442: \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438, \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430\u044f \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0430, \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0438, \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f|work=militaryparitet.com|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626192300/http://www.militaryparitet.com/vp/65/|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>)\n* number of targets for attack: 6 (was originally 4<ref name=\"militaryparitet.com\" /><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31bm.php|title=\u041c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0446\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c \u2013 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0430|work=worldweapon.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720051742/http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31bm.php|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>)\n* range of automatic tracking: {{convert|120|km|mi}}\n* detection of [[infrared signature]] targets: {{convert|56|km|mi}}\n* Effective in the detection of cruise missiles and other targets against [[Clutter (radar)|ground clutter]]<ref name=\"militaryparitet.com\" />\n* Until 2000, it was the world's only fighter in service equipped with phased array radar,<ref name=\"worldweapon.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31.php|title=\u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u2013 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0430|work=worldweapon.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720051731/http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31.php|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://militaryrussia.ru/blog/topic-407.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u2013 FOXHOUND|work=militaryrussia.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331101235/http://militaryrussia.ru/blog/topic-407.html|archive-date=31 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> when the [[Mitsubishi F-2]] entered service with the [[J/APG-1]] [[active phased array]] radar.\n* Able to intercept and destroy cruise missiles flying at extremely low altitudes.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milrus.com/vvs/mig31/text.shtml|title=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f. \u0418\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31. \u0412\u0422\u0420|website=www.milrus.com|access-date=19 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314135252/http://www.milrus.com/vvs/mig31/text.shtml|archive-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n=== Variant differences ===\nThe basic differences between other versions and the MiG-31BM are:<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n*The onboard radar complex of the MiG-31BM can track 24 airborne targets at one time, six of which can be simultaneously attacked by [[R-33 (missile)|R-33S]] missiles.<!-- R-37 on tests<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missiles.ru/RVV-BD.htm|title=missiles.ru :: \u041c\u0410\u041a\u0421-2011 - \u0420\u0412\u0412-\u0411\u0414 \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445-\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|work=missiles.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515013511/http://www.missiles.ru/RVV-BD.htm|archive-date=15 May 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>-->\n*Modernized variants of the aircraft can be equipped with anti-radiation missiles [[Kh-31]], [[Kh-25]]MR or MPU (up to six units), anti-ship Kh-31A (up to six), air-to-surface class missiles [[Kh-29]] and [[Kh-59]] (up to three) or Kh-59M (up to two units), up to six precision bombs [[KAB-1500]] or eight [[KAB-500]] with television or laser-guidance. Maximum mass of payload is {{convert|9000|kg|lb}}.{{Citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n*The MiG-31M, MiG-31D, and MiG-31BM standard aircraft have an upgraded ''Zaslon-M'' radar, with larger antenna and greater detection range (said to be {{convert|400|km|mi}} against [[Airborne Early Warning and Control|AWACS]]-size targets) and the ability to attack multiple targets&nbsp; \u2013 air and ground&nbsp;\u2013 simultaneously. The Zaslon-M has a {{convert|1.4|m|ft|abbr=on}} diameter (larger) antenna, with 50\u2013100% better performance than Zaslon. In April 1994 it was used with an [[Vympel R-37|R-37]] to hit a target at {{convert|300|km|mi}} distance.<ref name=\"milrus.com\" /> It has a search range of 400&nbsp;km for a 19\u201320 m<sup>2</sup> RCS target and can track 24 targets at once, engaging six,<ref name=\"Janes Defence\">[http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Avionics/N007-Zaslon-Fire-Control-Radar-FCR-Russian-Federation.html Zaslon radar] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130126154828/http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Avionics/N007-Zaslon-Fire-Control-Radar-FCR-Russian-Federation.html |date=26 January 2013 }} at Janes Defence web-site</ref><ref name=\"Russia Airforce Handbook\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kt2ZaOilGXIC&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=Zaslon-M+range&source=bl&ots=vPFShK0FM_&sig=AuHW9UIACYWZ2LlsJdViUGMsGz0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ykr5T8zdDYvRrQfH58jYBg&ved=0CGIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Zaslon-M%20range&f=false Zaslon radar] at Russia Airforce Handbook \u2013 Google Books</ref> or 282&nbsp;km for five&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"Radar Ranges\">[http://www.angelfire.com/falcon/fighterplanes/texts/articles/bestfighter.html \"Zaslon-M radar.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102204631/http://www.angelfire.com/falcon/fighterplanes/texts/articles/bestfighter.html |date=2 November 2013 }} ''Fighterplanes.'' Retrieved: 16 July 2012.</ref> Relative target speed detection increased from Mach 5 to Mach 6, improving the probability of destroying fast-moving targets.<ref name=\"milrus.com\" /> The MiG-31BM is one of only a few aircraft able to intercept and destroy cruise missiles flying at extremely low altitude.<ref name=\"milrus.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mig31.ucoz.ru/|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413 31 \u2013 \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0445\u0437\u0432\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c|work=ucoz.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720051938/http://mig31.ucoz.ru/|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arms-expo.ru/news/archive/60-istrebiteley-perehvatchikov-mig-31-budut-modernizirovany-do-2020-goda01-01-2012-10-04-00/?sphrase_id=2636609|title=60 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u0434\u043e 2020 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|work=arms-expo.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720081024/http://www.arms-expo.ru/news/archive/60-istrebiteley-perehvatchikov-mig-31-budut-modernizirovany-do-2020-goda01-01-2012-10-04-00/?sphrase_id=2636609|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Cockpit ===\n[[File:Cockpit of Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31 (2).jpg|thumb|Front seat cockpit of older MiG-31 variant]]\n\nThe aircraft is a two-seater with the rear seat occupant controlling the radar. Although cockpit controls are duplicated across cockpits, it is normal for the aircraft to be flown only from the front seat. The pilot flies the aircraft by means of a [[centre stick]] and left hand [[throttle]]s. The rear cockpit has only two small vision ports on the sides of the canopy. The presence of the WSO (weapon systems operator) in the rear cockpit improves aircraft effectiveness since the WSO is entirely dedicated to radar operations and weapons deployment, thus decreasing the workload of the pilot and increasing efficiency. Both cockpits are fitted with zero/zero [[ejection seat]]s which allow the crew to eject at any altitude and airspeed.<ref name=\"Dawes\" />\n\n=== Armament ===\n[[File:MiG-31 Foxhound aircraft armed with AA-9 missiles in flight.jpg|thumb|MiG-31 armed with [[R-33 (missile)|R-33]] missiles]]\n\nThe MiG-31's main armament is four [[Vympel R-33|R-33]] [[air-to-air missile]]s ([[NATO]] codename AA-9 'Amos') carried under the belly. \n*One [[Gryazev-Shipunov GSh-6-23|GSh-6-23]] 23&nbsp;mm cannon with 260 rounds.\n*Fuselage recesses for four [[R-33 (missile)|R-33 (AA-9 'Amos')]] or six [[R-37 (missile)|R-37 (AA-13 'Arrow')]] (MiG-31M/BM only).\n*Four underwing pylons for a combination of (six places for charging<ref>{{cite web|url=http://samolet-mig-31.narod.ru|title=\u0422\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u043a\u043e-\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0413-31|author=\u0414\u0440\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d|work=narod.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021075126/http://samolet-mig-31.narod.ru/|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> (two spaces to add removable fuel tanks<ref name=\"encyclopaedia-russia.ru\" />)):\n**Six [[R-37 (missile)]] long-range missiles {{convert|280|km|mi}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c|work=airwar.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709015818/http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|archive-date=9 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**Four<ref name=\"arms-expo.ru\" />) [[R-33 (missile)]] long-range missiles {{convert|300|km|mi}} 2012.<ref name=\"dokwar.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://dokwar.ru/publ/aviacija_i_flot/mig_31bm_poluchat_novuju_raketu/15-1-0-583|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0443|work=dokwar.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027091756/http://dokwar.ru/publ/aviacija_i_flot/mig_31bm_poluchat_novuju_raketu/15-1-0-583|archive-date=27 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** (?)\u00d7 Kh-31 long-range missiles (200&nbsp;km) for high-speed target (maneuvering with an overload of 8&nbsp;G).<ref name=\"dokwar.ru\" />\n** (?)\u00d7 R-33 AA-9 \"Amos\" (1981) {{convert|120|km|mi}}, R-33S (1999) {{convert|160|km|mi}}.<ref>http://\u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438.\u0440\u0444/russia/vympel/r/33/r33_1.htm {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027092514/http://xn--80akhcovnjb1g.xn--p1ai/russia/vympel/r/33/r33_1.htm |date=27 October 2014 }}</ref>\n**Two<ref name=\"arms-expo.ru\" /> or four (superior limit)<ref name=\"modernforces.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://www.modernforces.ru/mig-31b/|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411|work=modernforces.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429104802/http://www.modernforces.ru/mig-31b/|archive-date=29 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\u00d7 [[R-40 (missile)|R-40TD1 (AA-6 'Acrid')]] medium-range missiles (R-40 ({{convert|50|km|mi}}, MiG-25P, 1970) {{convert|80|km|mi}}(PD)(user)), height of applications between {{convert|0.5|-|3|km|mi}} (maneuvering with overload four&nbsp;g).<ref>http://\u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438.\u0440\u0444/russia/bisnovat/r/40/r40.htm {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422073038/http://xn--80akhcovnjb1g.xn--p1ai/russia/bisnovat/r/40/r40.htm |date=22 April 2016 }}</ref>\n**Four [[R-60 (missile)|R-60 (AA-8 'Aphid')]]\n***Four [[R-73 (missile)|R-73 (AA-11 'Archer')]] short-range IR missiles,\n***Four [[R-77]] (AA-12 'Adder') medium-range missiles (100 km) for high-speed target (maneuvering with overload of 12 G).<ref>http://\u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438.\u0440\u0444/russia/vympel/r/77/r77.htm {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510150627/http://xn--80akhcovnjb1g.xn--p1ai/russia/vympel/r/77/r77.htm |date=10 May 2017 }}</ref>\n*Some aircraft are equipped to launch the [[AS-17 Krypton|Kh-31P (AS-17 'Krypton')]] and [[AS-11 Kilter|Kh-58 (AS-11 'Kilter')]] [[anti-radiation missile]]s in the [[Suppression of Enemy Air Defenses]] (SEAD) role. Anti-ship missiles [[Kh-31]]A (up to six) and air-to-surface missiles X-59 and X-29T (up to three) or X-59M (up to two units), up to six air bombs KAB-1500, or up to eight KAB-500 with a television or laser-guidance. Maximum weight of the combat load is {{convert|9000|kg|lb}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31.php|title=\u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u2013 \u0412\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0430|website=worldweapon.ru|access-date=19 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720051731/http://worldweapon.ru/sam/mig31.php|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c|website=www.airwar.ru|access-date=19 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709015818/http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|archive-date=9 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*One [[Kh-47M2 Kinzhal]] high-precision hypersonic aeroballistic missile with a range of about 2,000 km, Mach 10 speed, and an ability to maneuver at every stage of flight.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.ru/russia/602049|script-title=ru:\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0412\u041a\u0421 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u0433\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0432\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430 \"\u041a\u0438\u043d\u0436\u0430\u043b\"|trans-title=Commander of the Aerospace Forces talks about Kinzhal hypersonic system specs|language=Russian|work=Interfax|location=Moscow|date=2018-03-01|access-date=2018-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302110759/http://www.interfax.ru/russia/602049|archive-date=2 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{vs|date=April 2018}} It can carry both conventional and nuclear warheads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180311/1516113028.html|title=\"\u041d\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 \u0443\u0436\u0430\u0441\": Daily Star \u043e\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e \u043f\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430 \"\u041a\u0438\u043d\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0430\"|date=11 March 2018|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229171625/https://ria.ru/20180311/1516113028.html|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This gave the MiG-31 long range strike capabilities for the first time, alongside its primary interceptor role. <ref>https://militarywatchmagazine.com/article/why-russian-adversaries-still-fear-the-mig-31-how-the-foxhoud-became-one-of-the-most-dangerous-combat-aircraft-in-the-world</ref>\n\n== Operational history ==\n[[File:MiG-31 790 IAP Khotilovo airbase.jpg|thumb|A side view of a MiG-31 from 790th Fighter Order of Kutuzov Aviation Regiment on the runway of Khotilovo airbase, Tver region.]]\n[[File:Mikoyan MiG-31 Foxhound formation - Zhukovsky 2012 (8710851439).jpg|thumb|A MiG-31B on left and MiG-31BM on right flying in formation.]]\n\nSerial production of the MiG-31 began in 1979.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tass.ru/politika/1369019|title=\u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d: \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u0435\u0449\u0435 15 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0412\u0412\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229171526/https://tass.ru/politika/1369019|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The MiG-31 entered operational service with the [[Soviet Air Defence Forces]] (PVO) in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/mig31.htm|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31|work=testpilot.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015170845/http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/mig31.htm|archive-date=15 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was the world's first aircraft with a [[phased array radar]], and is one of only two aircraft in the world capable of independently firing long-range [[air-to-air missile]]s as of 2013.<ref name=\"ria.ru\" /><ref name=\"auto\" /><ref name=\"auto1\" /> (The other is the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force|Iranian Air Force]] [[F-14 Tomcat in Iranian Service|F-14 Tomcat]] which uses a domestic version of the long-range [[AIM-54 Phoenix#Variants|AIM-54 Phoenix]] called the [[Fakour-90]].<ref name=\"auto2\" /><ref name=\"auto3\" />) The MiG-31BM has a detection range of 282&nbsp;km for a target with a [[radar cross-section]] of 5 square meters.\n\nWith the designation Ye-266, a re-engined Ye-155<ref>{{cite web|last1=Babain|first1=Sergey|title=E-155M (E-266M) \"FoxBat\" interceptor/recco-bomber|url=http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/25/m/mig25m_e.htm|website=TestPilot.ru|publisher=SB|accessdate=10 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017171136/http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/25/m/mig25m_e.htm|archive-date=17 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gordon|first1=Yefim|last2=Komissarov|first2=Dmitriy|title=Soviet spyplanes of the Cold War|date=2013|isbn=978-1-78159-285-4|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u8s7BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=7 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017171135/https://books.google.com/books?id=u8s7BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=17 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> set new world records.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kopp|first1=Dr. Carlo|title=Foxbat and Foxhound Russia's Cold War Warriors|url=http://www.ausairpower.net/TE-Foxbat-Foxhound-92.html|website=Aus Air Power|publisher=First published Australian Aviation, November, 1992|accessdate=7 October 2015|date=November 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923190608/http://www.ausairpower.net/TE-Foxbat-Foxhound-92.html|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It reached an [[Flight altitude record#Jet aircraft|absolute maximum altitude]] of {{convert|37,650|m|ft|abbr=off}} in 1977,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boyne|first1=Walter J.|title=Beyond the wild blue a history of the U.S. Air Force, 1947\u20132007|date=2013|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=1-4299-0180-2|page=493|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EmgLHStZPhkC&pg=PA493#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017171135/https://books.google.com/books?id=EmgLHStZPhkC&pg=PA493#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=17 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and set a time to height record of {{convert|35,000|m|ft|abbr=off}} in 4 minutes, 11.78 seconds, both of which were set by the famous MiG test pilot Alexander Fedotov. Pyotr Ostapenko,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ankov|first1=Vitaly|title=MiG Test Pilot Ostapenko Dies Age 83|url=http://sputniknews.com/russia/20120409/172706896.html|website=Sputnik News|publisher=Sputnik|accessdate=10 October 2015|date=9 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105112629/http://sputniknews.com/russia/20120409/172706896.html|archive-date=5 January 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> his deputy, set a time to height record to {{convert|30,000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in 3 minutes and 9.8 seconds in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flight Global Archive \u2013 Aviation History 1975|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1975/1975%20-%200951.html|website=Flight Global|publisher=Flight International|accessdate=10 October 2015|page=855|date=29 May 1975|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017171135/https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1975/1975%20-%200951.html|archive-date=17 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://wp.scn.ru/mig_okb/his-10 \"World Records.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928054542/http://wp.scn.ru/mig_okb/his-10 |date=28 September 2011 }} ''OKB MIG.'' Retrieved: 11 May 2011.</ref>{{clarify |date=July 2017 |reason = Is that really for MiG-31? Same sentence about exactly same records and for same year appears in article for [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25#Record breaker | MiG-25]].}}\n\nOn 26 April 2017, a MiG-31 crashed during a training exercise over the Telemba proving ground in [[Buryatia]]; both crew members successfully ejected.<ref name=\"MiG-31 interceptor jet crashes in Russia\">{{cite|title = MiG-31 interceptor jet crashes in Russia|url = https://tass.com/defense/943304|publisher = TASS|date = 26 April 2017|accessdate = 5 September 2019}}</ref> While Russian state media did not offer any details, independent investigators discovered from a leaked government document that the aircraft was in fact shot down by an R-33 missile fired from another MiG-31, and that [[pilot error]] from both planes were at fault. The report also suggested problems with the Zaslon-AM radar and Baget-55 fire control system that might increase the risk of more accidental shootdowns occurring in the future.<ref name=\"Russian MiG-31 Foxhound Shot Down Its Wingman During Disastrous Live Fire Exercise\">{{cite|title = Russian MiG-31 Foxhound Shot Down Its Wingman During Disastrous Live Fire Exercise|url = https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/27620/russian-mig-31-foxhound-shot-down-its-wingman-during-disastrous-live-fire-exercise|publisher = The Drive|author = Joseph Trevithick|date = 23 April 2019|accessdate = 5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Export ===\n[[Syria]] ordered eight MiG-31E aircraft in 2007 for the [[Syrian Air Force]].<ref>''[[Air Forces Monthly]]'', August 2007 issue</ref><ref>Karnozov, Vladimir. [http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2007/06/21/215106/syria-signs-for-eight-mig-31-interceptors.html \"Syria signs for eight MiG-31 interceptors.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220024704/http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2007/06/21/215106/syria-signs-for-eight-mig-31-interceptors.html |date=20 December 2007 }} ''Flight International'', 21 June 2007.</ref>  The order was suspended in May 2009 reportedly either due to Israeli pressure or lack of Syrian funds.<ref>[https://archive.is/20110604025000/http://www.mosnews.com/money/2009/05/20/tosyria/ \"Syrian MiG-31 Order suspended.\"] ''mosnews.com.'' Retrieved: 24 January 2011.</ref>  On 15 August 2015, Turkish news media reported that six MiG-31s had been delivered to the Syrian Arab Air Force,<ref>{{cite web |title=Russia delivers six Mikoyan MiG-31 fighter jets to Syria: Report |date=16 Aug 2015 |work=Press TV |url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2015/08/16/425037/Russia-Iraq-Syria-Mikoyan-MiG31-Rosoboronexport |quote=According to a Sunday report by Turkey's English-language website BGN News, Moscow shipped the supersonic interceptor aircraft to Damascus under a contract inked between the two sides in 2007 |access-date=17 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817015624/http://presstv.com/Detail/2015/08/16/425037/Russia-Iraq-Syria-Mikoyan-MiG31-Rosoboronexport |archive-date=17 August 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2015/08/16/425037/Russia-Iraq-Syria-Mikoyan-MiG31-Rosoboronexport|title=Russia delivers 6 MiG-31 jets to Syria|date=16 August 2015|work=PressTV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817133700/http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2015/08/16/425037/Russia-Iraq-Syria-Mikoyan-MiG31-Rosoboronexport|archive-date=17 August 2015}}</ref> but Russia denied making MiG-31 deliveries to Syria.<ref>{{cite web |title=No MiG-31s for Damascus: Russia Denies Sending Interceptors to Syria |date=22 Aug 2015 |work=Sputnik News |url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20150822/1026049778/no-mig-31-for-syria.html |access-date=15 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910021638/http://sputniknews.com/military/20150822/1026049778/no-mig-31-for-syria.html |archive-date=10 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Variants ==\n[[File:MiG-31 790 IAP Khotilovo airbase 2.jpg|thumb|A front view of a MiG-31 on the ramp of Khotilovo airbase, Tver region]]\n\n;Ye-155MP (MiG-25MP): Prototype modification of the early MiG-31. First flight in 16 September 1975.\n\n;MiG-31: First variant which entered in serial production. 349 aircraft were built.\n\n;MiG-31M: Development of a more comprehensive advanced version, the MiG-31M, began in 1984 and first flew in 1985, but the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] prevented it from entering full production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/m/mig31m.htm|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u041c|work=testpilot.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210140156/http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/m/mig31m.htm|archive-date=10 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Russian MiG-31 \"Foxhound\" \u2013 A fighter ahead of its time|url=http://globalaviationreport.com/2014/02/21/russian-mig-31-foxhound-a-fighter-ahead-of-its-time/|website=Global Aviation Report|publisher=WordPress|accessdate=12 July 2015|date=21 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713060235/http://globalaviationreport.com/2014/02/21/russian-mig-31-foxhound-a-fighter-ahead-of-its-time/|archive-date=13 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One piece rounded windscreen, small side windows for rear cockpit, wider and deeper dorsal spine. Digital flight controls added, multifunction CRT cockpit displays, multi-mode phased array radar. No gun fitted in this model, refueling probe moved to starboard side of aircraft, fuselage weapon stations increased from 4 to 6 by adding two centre-line stations. Maximum TO weight increased to 52,000&nbsp;kg using increased thrust D-30F6M engines instead of the D-30F6 engines.<ref name=Janes1998 /> 1 prototype and 6 flyable pre-production units were produced.\n\n;MiG-31D: Two aircraft were designated as Type 31D and were manufactured as dedicated anti-satellite models with ballast in the nose instead of radars, flat fuselage undersurface (i.e. no recessed weapon system bays) and had large winglets above and below the wing-tips. Equipped with Vympel [[Anti-satellite weapon|ASAT]] missiles.<ref name=Janes1998 /> Two prototypes were built.\n\n;MiG-31LL: Special modification used as a flying laboratory for testing of ejection seats during flight.\n\n;MiG-31 01DZ: Two-seat all weather, all altitude interceptor. Designated as MiG-31 01DZ when fitted with air-to-air refueling probe.<ref name=Janes1998>{{cite book|editor1-last=Jackson|editor1-first=Paul|title=Jane's: All the World's Aircraft: 1998\u201399|date=1998|publisher=Jane's|location=Surrey|isbn=0-7106-1788-7|page=386}}</ref> One hundred produced of DZ variant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31dz.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0414\u0417|website=www.airwar.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205145758/http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31dz.html|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;MiG-31B: Second production batch with upgraded [[avionics]] and in-flight refueling probe introduced in 1990. Its development was the result of the Soviet discovery that [[Phazotron]] [[radar]] division engineer [[Adolf Tolkachev]] had sold information on advanced radars to the West. A new version of the compromised radar was hastily developed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/b/mig31b.htm|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411 (\u0411\u0421)|work=testpilot.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724160048/http://www.testpilot.ru/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/b/mig31b.htm|archive-date=24 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  MiG-31B also have the improved ECM and EW equipment with integration of improved R-33S missiles.  Long range navigation system compatible with Loran/Omega and Chaka ground stations added. This model replaced the 01DZ models in late 1990.<ref name=Janes1998 />\n\n;MiG-31E: Export version of the MiG-31B with simplified avionics. Never entered in serial production.<ref name=Janes1998 />\n\n;MiG-31BS: Designation applied to type 01DZ when converted to MiG-31B standard.<ref name=Janes1998 />\n\n;MiG-31BM: After passing state testing in 2008 this modernized variant of MiG-31B was approved for introduction into air force of Russia. 50 planes are modified to MiG-31BM (Bolshaya Modernizatsiya/Deep Modernization) standard in accordance with 2011 contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aviaport.ru/news/2014/11/28/316847.html|title=\u041e\u0410\u041a \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 (\u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442)|website=\u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442.Ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193408/https://www.aviaport.ru/news/2014/11/28/316847.html|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Efficiency of modernized MiG-31BM is 2.6 times greater than basic MiG-31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defencetalk.com/24-mig-31bm-fighter-jets-commissioned-for-the-russian-armed-forces-63839/|title=24 MiG-31BM Fighter Jets Commissioned for the Russian Armed Forces - DefenceTalk.com|last=DefenceTalk|website=www.defencetalk.com|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702234000/https://www.defencetalk.com/24-mig-31bm-fighter-jets-commissioned-for-the-russian-armed-forces-63839/|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The MiG-31B\u041c's maximum detection range for air targets was increased in the upgrade to 320&nbsp;km. It had the ability to automatically track up to ten targets, and the latest units can track up to 24 targets and simultaneously engage up to eight targets. The on-board Argon-K is replaced with new Baget 55-06 computer<ref name=\"flugrevue1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.flugrevue.de/militaerluftfahrt/kampfflugzeuge-helikopter/mikojan-mig-31bm-mit-neuen-waffen-und-systemen/523610|title=Modernisierung: Mikojan MiG-31BM mit neuen Waffen und Systemen|website=FLUG REVUE|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917061831/http://www.flugrevue.de/militaerluftfahrt/kampfflugzeuge-helikopter/mikojan-mig-31bm-mit-neuen-waffen-und-systemen/523610|archive-date=17 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> that selects four targets of highest priority, which simultaneously are engaged by long-range [[R-33 (missile)|R-33S]] air-to-air missiles.<ref>[http://www.testpilots.ru/tp/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/mig31_1_e.htm MiG-31. The description of a design, Specification and scheme.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006011730/http://www.testpilots.ru/tp/russia/mikoyan/mig/31/mig31_1_e.htm |date=6 October 2017 }}</ref> New long range missile [[R-37 (missile)]] with speed of Mach 6 and range up to 400 km is developed during modernization process for use with newly modernized MiG-31.<ref name=\"flugrevue1\"/> MiG-31BM has multi-role capability as is capable of using anti-radar, air to ship and air to ground missiles. It has some of avionics unified with MiG-29SMT and has refueling probe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c|website=airwar.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193341/http://airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bm.html|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> MiG-31BM broke world record while spending seven hours and four minutes in the air while covering the distance of 8,000 km.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20160408/1404918600.html|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434 \u0434\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c|date=8 April 2016|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229171620/https://ria.ru/20160408/1404918600.html|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;MiG-31BSM: An upgrade of the BS version, it is the latest modernization variant first time contracted in 2014 for modernization of 60 aircraft, it is very similar in some aspects to the BM standard. Unlike the BS standard, aircraft modernized into the BSM standard are equipped with air refueling probe. Improvements were made to the aircraft canopy, where new and better heat resistant glass was used, thus enabling the MiG-31BSM to fly with cruise speed of 3000 km/h at long distances without any damage. Furthermore, new faster central computer Baget-55-06 is used with addition of multi-functional displays, one for pilot and three for weapons operator-navigator. Also there is a new set of navigation equipment. The MiG-31BSM has multi-role capability with ability to use anti-radar, anti-ship and air-to-ground missiles. Main visible difference between the BS and BSM standards is adding of the rear-view periscope above the front cockpit canopy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bsm.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0414\u0417|website=airwar.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805053506/http://www.airwar.ru/enc/fighter/mig31bsm.html|archive-date=5 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;MiG-31K: Modified MiG-31BM variant capable to carry the hypersonic [[Kh-47M2 Kinzhal]] [[air-launched ballistic missile|ALBM]]. Ten aircraft have been modified as of May 2018.<ref name=\"MiG-31K in service\">{{cite web|url=http://tass.com/defense/1002992|title=Ten MIG-31 fighter jets fitted with Kinzhal air-launched missiles on test combat duty|website=[[TASS]]|date=5 May 2018|accessdate=18 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019024950/http://tass.com/defense/1002992|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With this modification and with removed APU for air-to-air missiles, the aircraft gained a sole role of an attack aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://theaviationist.com/2018/05/05/russia-shows-new-hypersonic-cruise-missile-on-two-mig-31-aircraft-in-victory-day-rehearsals/|title=Russia Shows New Hypersonic Missile on Two MiG-31 Aircraft in Victory Day Rehearsals|date=2018-05-05|work=The Aviationist|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507083351/https://theaviationist.com/2018/05/05/russia-shows-new-hypersonic-cruise-missile-on-two-mig-31-aircraft-in-victory-day-rehearsals/|archive-date=7 May 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.com/defense/998221|title=ussia picks MiG-31 fighter as a carrier for cutting-edge hypersonic weapon|website=[[TASS]]|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=18 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811220202/http://tass.com/defense/998221|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n;MiG-31F: Planned fighter-bomber intended for use with TV, radar and laser-guided ASM weapon systems. Never entered in serial production.<ref name=Janes1998 />\n\n;MiG-31FE: Planned export version of the MiG-31F.<ref name=Janes1998 />\n\n;MiG-31I (Ishim): Modification for [[air launch to orbit]] of small spacecraft with a mass of 120\u2013160 kg to Earth's orbit in altitude about 600\u2013300 km.\n\n;MiG-31 (Izd.08): Modified MiG-31 to transport the  new [[anti-satellite missile]] Izd. 293<ref>e-maksimov.livejounral.com/104856.html</ref>.\n\n== Operators ==\n[[File:MiG-31 operators.png|thumb|Map with operators of the MiG-31 in blue and former operators in red]]\n\n;{{KAZ}}\n* [[Armed Forces of the Republic of Kazakhstan|Kazakhstan Air Force]] \u2013 25 in inventory as of 2017.<ref name=WorldAirForces2017/>\n;{{RUS}}\n* [[Russian Aerospace Forces]]\n** [[Russian Air Force]] \u2013 about 250 in inventory<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvzvezda.ru/news/opk/content/201610131239-9m8w.htm |title=\u0412\u041a\u0421 \u0420\u0424 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0442 22 \u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c \u0434\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |publisher=tvzvezd.ru |date=13 October 2016 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814220505/https://tvzvezda.ru/news/opk/content/201610131239-9m8w.htm |archive-date=14 August 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ria.ru/defense_safety/20170825/1501120951.html |title=\u041e\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0435\u0446: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u043c \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0449\u0438\u043a \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 |publisher=ria.ru |date=28 August 2017 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022244/https://ria.ru/defense_safety/20170825/1501120951.html |archive-date=7 November 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and approximately 120-132 (MiG-31B/BS/BM/BSM) in service as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bmpd.livejournal.com/2326878.html |title=\u0412\u041a\u0421 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u0442\u044c 700 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 |publisher=bmpd.livejournal.com |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027050237/http://bmpd.livejournal.com/2326878.html |archive-date=27 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=WorldAirForces2017>{{cite web |url=https://flightglobal.com/asset/6297/waf/ |title=World Air Forces 2017 |publisher=Flightglobal Insight |date=2017 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119005850/https://flightglobal.com/asset/6297/waf/ |archive-date=19 January 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Modernization of the MiG-31s is carried out by the [[Sokol Aircraft Plant]] under two contracts signed in 2011 and 2014. In total, 113 aircraft will be modernized to the MiG-31BM/BSM standards by the end of 2018\u20132019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=12001898@egNews |title=\u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u041e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)]] |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107012007/http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=12001898@egNews |archive-date=7 November 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=12099552 |title=\u0417\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0431\u044b\u043b \u0441 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0435\u0437\u0434\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0432 \u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Russia)]] |date=13 October 2016 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814145156/http://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=12099552 |archive-date=14 August 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Approximately 110 aircraft were modernized as of August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bmpd.livejournal.com/2784601.html |title=\u041e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u041c\u0438\u0413-31\u0411\u041c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0432 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0423\u0433\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e |publisher=bmpd.livejournal.com |date=13 August 2017 |accessdate=3 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015180058/http://bmpd.livejournal.com/2784601.html |archive-date=15 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ten jets have been modified to the MiG-31K version and carry the Kh-47M2 Kinzhal missile as of May 2018.<ref name=\"MiG-31K in service\"/>\n* [[Russian Naval Aviation]] \u2013 32 in inventory as of 2016.<ref>The Military Balance 2016.  p. 193.</ref>\n\n=== Former operators ===\n;{{USSR}}\n* [[Soviet Air Forces]] aircraft passed to the Russian and Kazakhstan Air Forces after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]].\n* [[Soviet Air Defence Forces]]\n\n== Notable accidents ==\nOn 4 April 1984, a MiG-31 crashed while on a test flight, killing Mikoyan chief test pilot and Hero of the Soviet Union, [[Aleksandr Vasilyevich Fedotov]] and his navigator V. Zaitsev.{{fact|date=November 2018}}\n\nOn 16 April 2020, a MiG-31 interceptor aircraft of the Kazakhstan Air Force crashed in the country\u2019s Karaganda region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenseworld.net/news/26764|title=Kazakhstan Air Force MiG-31 Crashes, Pilots Bail Out|website=www.defenseworld.net|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications (MiG-31) ==\n[[File:MiG-31.svg|thumb|350px|right|]]\n[[File:MiG-31BM on the MAKS-2009 (01).jpg|thumb|MiG-31BM on display at [[MAKS Air Show]] on 22 August 2009]]\n[[File:Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31E at MAKS 2005.jpg|thumb|right|MiG-31E at 2005 MAKS Air Show]]\n[[File:Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31E landing at Sormovo (2007).jpg|thumb|right|MiG-31E landing at [[Sormovo Airfield]], 2007]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Great Book of Modern Warplanes,<ref name=\"Great Book\">Spick 2000</ref> Mikoyan,<ref name=\"MiG-31E page\">[http://www.migavia.ru/index.php/en/production/mig-31e-fighter] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001112123/http://www.migavia.ru/index.php/en/production/mig-31e-fighter |date=1 October 2015 }} ''RAC MiG.'' Retrieved: 22 July 2008.</ref> Combat Aircraft since 1945,<ref name=Wilson>Wilson 2000, p.&nbsp;103.</ref> airforce-technology.com,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.airforce-technology.com/projects/mig-31/ |title=MiG-31 Foxhound Interceptor Aircraft |website=airforce-technology.com |accessdate=29 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229171359/https://www.airforce-technology.com/projects/mig-31/ |archive-date=29 December 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> deagel.com<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deagel.com/Combat-Aircraft/Mig-31_a000358001.aspx|title=Mig-31|website=deagel.com|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229134806/http://www.deagel.com/Combat-Aircraft/Mig-31_a000358001.aspx|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|prime units?=met\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|crew=2 (pilot and weapons systems officer)\n|length m=22.62\n|length note=\n|span m=13.456\n|span note=\n|height m=6.456\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=61.6\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|airfoil=<!--'''root:''' [[NACA airfoil|NACA ]]; '''tip:''' [[NACA airfoil|NACA ]]<ref name=\"Selig\">{{cite web |last1=Lednicer |first1=David |title=The Incomplete Guide to Airfoil Usage |url=https://m-selig.ae.illinois.edu/ads/aircraft.html |website=m-selig.ae.illinois.edu |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>-->\n|empty weight kg=21820\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=41000\n|gross weight note=\n|max takeoff weight kg=46200\n|max takeoff weight note=\n|fuel capacity={{convert|35550|lb|kg|abbr=on}} internals, plus optional external fuel tanks<ref name=\"aviationweek.com\"/>\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 name=[[Soloviev D-30]]F6\n|eng1 type=[[afterburning]] [[turbofan]] engines\n|eng1 kn=93\n|eng1 note=\n|eng1 kn-ab=152\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|max speed kmh=3000\n|max speed note=at {{cvt|21500|m|0}} / Mach 2.83\n::::{{cvt|1500|km/h|mph kn}} / Mach 1.21 at low altitude\n|max speed mach=\n|cruise speed kmh=2500\n|cruise speed note= / Mach 2.35\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|minimum control speed kmh=\n|minimum control speed note=\n|range km=3000\n|range note=with 4 x R-33E and 2 drop tanks\n:::{{cvt|5400|km|mi nmi}} with 4 x R-33E and 2 drop tanks with one aerial refueling<ref name=\"migavia.ru\">{{cite web |url=http://www.migavia.ru/index.php/en/production/mig-31e-fighter?limit=1&start=2 |title=MiG-31E fighter |first=Super |last=User |website=migavia.ru |access-date=30 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001100055/http://www.migavia.ru/index.php/en/production/mig-31e-fighter?limit=1&start=2 |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|combat range km=1450\n|combat range note=at Mach 0.8 and {{cvt|10000|m|0}}\n::::{{cvt|720|km|mi nmi}} at Mach 2.35 and {{cvt|18000|m|0}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roe.ru/cataloque/air_craft/aircraft_16-19.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308124035/http://www.roe.ru/cataloque/air_craft/aircraft_16-19.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-08|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=8 March 2012|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n|ferry range km=\n|ferry range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=25000\n|ceiling note=<big>+</big><ref>{{cite web|url=http://csef.ru/en/oborona-i-bezopasnost/423/boj-v-blizhnem-kosmose-na-kakih-vysotah-sposoben-voevat-rossijskij-mig-31-7462|title=The combat in middle space: at what altitude are able to fight the Russian MiG-31|website=csef.ru|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004190117/http://csef.ru/en/oborona-i-bezopasnost/423/boj-v-blizhnem-kosmose-na-kakih-vysotah-sposoben-voevat-rossijskij-mig-31-7462|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|g limits=<big>+</big>5\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|climb rate ms=288\n|climb rate note=\n|time to altitude=\n|wing loading kg/m2=665\n|wing loading note=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|thrust/weight=0.85\n\n|more performance=\n<!--\n        Armament\n-->\n|guns=1 \u00d7 [[23\u00d7115mm|23 mm]] [[Gryazev-Shipunov GSh-6-23]]M [[rotary cannon]] with 800 rounds (later removed)\n|hardpoints=8 \u00d7 underwing pylons\n|hardpoint missiles=\n[[Air-to-air missile]]s:\n**4 \u00d7 [[R-33 (missile)|R-33]]E\n**4 \u00d7 [[R-60 (missile)|R-60]]MK\n**2 \u00d7 [[R-40 (missile)|R-40]]RD/TD\n*[[Air-to-surface missile]]s:\n**4 \u00d7 [[Kh-58]]UShKE [[anti-radiation missile]]\n**1 \u00d7 [[Kh-47M2 Kinzhal]] hypersonic [[air-launched ballistic missile]]\n<!--\n     Avionics -->\n|avionics=\n*8TK [[Infrared_search_and_track|IRST]]<ref>\"MiG-31 d\u00e1le rozv\u00edjen - MagnetPress\". www.vydavatelstvo-mps.sk.</ref>\n*[[Phazotron]] [[Zaslon]] [[passive electronically scanned array]] [[radar]]\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n{{aircontent\n|see also=<!-- other related articles that have not already linked: -->\n* [[Firefox (novel)|''Firefox'' (novel)]] and [[Firefox (film)|''Firefox'' (film)]], the premise of which is the theft of a speculated/fictional version of the MiG-31\n|related=<!-- designs which were developed into or from this aircraft: -->\n* [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25]]\n* [[Mikoyan MiG-41]]\n|similar aircraft=<!-- aircraft that are of similar role, era, and capability as this design: -->\n* [[Grumman F-14 Tomcat]]\n* [[McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle]]\n* [[Panavia Tornado ADV]]\n* [[Sukhoi Su-27]]\n|lists=<!-- relevant lists that this aircraft appears in: -->\n* [[List of military aircraft of the Soviet Union and the CIS]]\n<!-- See [[WP:Air/PC]] for more explanation of these fields. -->\n}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Crickmore, Paul F. [https://books.google.com/books?id=xwPFC3GtcL8C&printsec=frontcover ''Lockheed Blackbird: Beyond the Secret Missions''.] Oxford, UK: Osprey Publishing, 2004. {{ISBN|1-84176-694-1}}.\n* Eden, Paul, ed. \"Mikoyan MiG-25 'Foxbat'\". \"Mikoyan MiG-31 'Foxhound'\". ''Encyclopedia of Modern Military Aircraft''. London: Amber Books, 2004. {{ISBN|1-904687-84-9}}.\n* Gordon, Yefim. ''MiG-25 'Foxbat,' MiG-31 'Foxhound:\" Russia's Defensive Front Line''. Hinckley, UK: Midland Publishing, 1997. {{ISBN|1-85780-064-8}}.\n* Spick, Mike. \"MiG-31 'Foxhound'\". ''The Great Book of Modern Warplanes''. St. Paul, Minnesota: MBI, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7603-0893-4}}.\n* Wilson, Stewart. ''Combat Aircraft since 1945''. Fyshwick, Australia: Aerospace Publications, 2000. {{ISBN|1-875671-50-1}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-31}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080107063714/http://www.migavia.ru/eng/military_e/MiG_31_E_e.htm MiG-31E page on Russian Aircraft Corporation \"MiG\" site]\n*[http://www.milavia.net/aircraft/mig-31/mig-31.htm MiG-31 page on milavia.net]\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org